surveys.narrative: Fox Lake, near the town of Sherburn, is a 1041 acre lake in Martin County. Walleye and muskellunge are the primary species of management. Additionally, Fox Lake is managed secondarily for black and white crappie and channel catfish. Since 2001, the walleye catch rate has been somewhat lower than desired. In an effort to boost the walleye fishery, the Windom DNR Fisheries Office stocked 1556 pounds of walleye fingerlings in 2001 and 2103 pounds of walleye fingerlings in 2003. Muskellunge were stocked in 1999 and 2001 to create an additional fishery and potentially create a top-level predator on an abundant freshwater drum population. One more stocking of muskellunge was scheduled for the fall of 2003 but the ponds failed to produce. Fisheries personnel will evaluate the muskellunge introductions following the last stocking to decide if the plan is having the desired affect to the fish community. A population assessment was conducted the week of September 8, 2003 using 6 gill nets and 12 trap nets.The walleye catch rate was slightly better than the 2002 catch rate and within "normal" range. Most of the fish were good sized and averaged 21.5 inches. Four year classes of walleyes were sampled (1994, 1995, 1997, and 1998). Fox Lake has a history of natural reproduction and the walleye from 1994 and 1997 were from years in which natural reproduction was probably occurred. With the recent emphasis on walleye fingerling stocking and the typically higher survival of fingerling stockings, it is likely walleye numbers will increase in the next couple of years.Only 1 muskellunge was captured in a gill net during the 2003 survey. Personal contacts with local anglers indicate some muskies are being caught at times. According to the local anglers and commercial operators, most of the muskies are not quite 40 inches long, but are growing well and are in good condition. Remember that muskellunge that are not 40 inches long have to be returned to the water. The black crappie catch rate was higher than average. Total lengths ranged from 3.5 to 10.3 inches and averaged 7.1 inches. The black crappie size structure declined slightly from 2002 while the catch rates have not changed substantially since the last survey. Historically, Fox Lake crappie fishing has been excellent in the spring. Netting information indicated spring of 2004 should be great fishing. The white crappie catch rates was at least 5 times higher than the normal range. Most of the fish are in the 6-8 inch range and averaged close to 7 inches. The 2002 netting documented a large naturally reproduced year class of fish from 2001. That year class of fish averaged 6.4 inches long in 2002 and now are averaging 7.7 inches. If growth rates continue, fish should be close to 9 inches by fall of 2004. Crappie fishing could be excellent in another year for some real "slabs". Channel catfish were abundant in gill nets in 2003. Channel catfish have not been stocked since 1986 which means the population is self-sustaining. These fish could provide some exciting action on those hot summer days when the crappie and walleye are finicky. The freshwater drum catch rate in gill nets was 24.7/set which was typical and they averaged about 9 inches long. Since a lot fewer were sampled in 2003 than in 2002, it is possible that muskies may be using them for forage, which was a goal of stocking muskies in the first place. Future yearly monitoring of the drum and muskellunge populations may provide insight to the predator-prey relationship.A total of thirteen species of fish were captured during the survey of 2003. Other species captured were bigmouth buffalo, black bullhead, bluegill, common carp, northern pike, yellow bullhead, and yellow perch.To promote and maintain healthy fish populations, pollution and other inputs need to be controlled. Fish habitats are directly affected by water quality. Nutrient, sediment and other waste inputs can drastically alter the biological, chemical, and physical components of a lake. It is important to maintain if not improve the current water quality of Fox Lake through watershed management to preserve this fishery for future generations to enjoy. Prepared by Ryan Doorenbos

Fox Lake, near the town of Sherburn, is a 1,041 acre lake in Martin County. Walleye and muskellunge are the primary species of management. Fox Lake is managed secondarily for crappie and channel catfish. In an effort to bolster the walleye population, 2.6 tons of walleye fingerlings/adults have been stocked since 2001. A population assessment was conducted the week of September 12, 2005 using 6 gill nets and 12 trap nets.The walleye catch rate in Fox Lake has been similar for the last 4 surveys with catch rates below the expected range. Walleyes averaged over 15 inches in gill nets and over 18 inches in trap nets. There is some reason to believe that our netting information is not revealing a "true" picture of the walleye population. Our trap netting data indicated the population was greater than the expected range. It is possible that fall electrofishing or spring trap netting will provide a more accurate picture of the walleye population. Despite the low catch rates in gill nets, our trap netting data indicated a good "slug" of walleyes in the 20-26 inch range. A total of 6 muskellunge were captured in gill nets and trap nets during the 2005 survey. Nets failed to capture any fish greater than 40 inches, however commercial seining has documented several fish greater than 40 inches. Personal contacts with local anglers indicate that legal muskies are being caught. Ernie and Rick Hand have reported nearly 300 muskellunge in commercial fishing reports in 6 years of seining in Fox Lake. The commercial fishing reports provide good information on the success of muskie stocking and population status. Further cooperative work with the local commercial fishing operator will likely yield information on the success of the fishery. If an angler is looking for a unique opportunity to catch a muskie, it is likely it won't take "10,000" casts to get some action.The black crappie catch rate in trap nets was 14.8 fish/set, which was within the expected range (1.8 to 21.2 fish/set). Black crappies averaged nearly 8 inches in length and were in great condition. The last several years, white crappie catch rates have been greater than the black crappie. Based on growth analysis, it would appear the 2002 year class of white crappie, similar to black crappie, is abundant and continues to grow at a rate of 1-2 inches per year. Both species were quite "plump", which indicated the fish are growing well and in good health. Given the large population of crappies, this fishery seems to consistently provide a possibility at some great action, especially in the spring.The channel catfish catch rates have been similar for the last 3 years. Good numbers of channel catfish averaging 17.4 inches can provide some quality fishing during the heat of the summer. Channel catfish have not been stocked since 1986, which means the population is self-sustaining. If you are in the Sherburn area fishing and wanting to catch some catfish, it is likely this fishery would be worth your limited angler hours.Since 2002, we have captured only 2 common carp per gill net during the last 3 years of assessments on Fox Lake. Additionally, we have documented less than 1 common carp per trap net during the same time frame. It is possible that muskellunge are influencing reproduction and thereby controlling the numbers of common carp. Further assessments will be evaluated to see if this trend continues.Other species captured were bigmouth buffalo, black bullhead, bluegill, freshwater drum, northern pike, and yellow perch.To promote and maintain healthy fish populations, pollution and other inputs need to be controlled. Fish habitats are directly affected by water quality. Nutrient, sediment and other waste inputs can drastically alter the biological, chemical, and physical components of a lake. Fox Lake is a 1,041acre lake located in south-central Minnesota near the city of Sherburn in Martin County. Fox Lake has a maximum depth of 20 feet; however, roughly 75 percent of the lake is considered littoral (less than 15 ft deep). Minnesota lakes managed for fishing are grouped into classes based on physical and chemical similarities and Fox Lake is assigned to lake class 24. Lake class 24 consists of smaller, shallower, relatively turbid lakes high in nutrients, littoral area, and having irregular shape. The lake to watershed ratio for Fox Lake is 4 to 1, which indicates a relatively small influence of the watershed to the lake. The water clarity for Fox Lake has improved since the water diversion was welded shut. Other watershed improvements have facilitated the return of aquatic vegetation. Despite some recreational user complaints about the aquatic vegetation, the increased habitat has been good for the fish. Water clarity has returned as well; a 2.9 foot water transparency was observed during the summer of 2011.

Like many lakes in southern Minnesota, Fox Lake is managed primarily for walleye and secondarily for black and white crappie. However, Fox Lake is unique within the Windom Fish Management area because it is the only lake that is managed for muskellunge and the lake represents the southernmost muskellunge lake in the state, which provides a very unique angling opportunity. In addition, Fox Lake has been surveyed annually since 1991, which has provided an exceptional dataset to infer fish population trends and direct subsequent fish management decisions. Finally, unlike many lakes in southern Minnesota, Fox Lake has never been aerated during the winter and provides a more stable dissolved oxygen profile during winter when compared to other area lakes. Ultimately, Fox Lake has proven to be a valuable and unique resource in southern Minnesota for lakeshore owners, local and regional anglers, as well as general recreational users.


The management goals for Fox Lake are to maintain a walleye population at an abundance that will consistently yield gill net catches above 6 fish per net with a balanced size structure. Another management goal is to continue efforts to establish a fishery for trophy size (greater than 50 inches) muskellunge. Lastly, our goal is to maintain secondary populations of white or black crappie within normal ranges for trap net catches (0.5 to 6.6 fish per net for white crappie and 1.8 to 21.2 fish per net for black crappie). Populations of the above mentioned species will be maintained through stocking (walleye and muskellunge) or natural reproduction (white and black crappie). In order to assess the management goals for Fox Lake, a fish population assessment was conducted in September 2011 using trap nets and gill nets.


The walleye gill net catch rate in 2011 was 3.2 fish per net, which was within the normal range for lake class 24 (1.2 to 6.3 fish per net). In the same way, the trap net catch rate was 0.9 fish per net which was within the normal range of 0.3 to 1.2 fish per net. With that said, the catch rate did not meet the management goal of 6 fish per net. Total length of walleye in the gill nets had an average length of 12.8 inches and ranged from 11.4 to 16.7 inches. The gill net and trap net sample indicated a population of walleye that is dominated by fish smaller than 15 inches. Walleye stocking in Fox Lake has usually been done with fingerlings (late development age 0 fish between 6 and 10 inches), but in 2010 and 2011 oxytetracycline (OTC) marked frylings (2 to 4 inches) were stocked. It appears the fryling stockings were successful, but growth was slow. Age 0 walleye had an average length of 6.7 inches, age 1 were 11.4 inches, age 2 were 12.5 inches, age 3 were 13.7 inches, age 4 were 14.0 inches and age 5 were 16.7 inches. The overall condition of the walleye was fair indicating a population of fish that is in below average condition. Overall, it appears that the walleye population is at a low abundance and may be experiencing growth problems as a result of foraging stress during their first 3 years. Continued stocking of frylings may boost the walleye abundance if blank stocking years are included to increase forage abundance through decreased competition for food.



The muskellunge catch rates in 2011 were 0.2 fish per gill net and 0.3 fish per trap net, which are below the normal gill net (0.3 to 1.0 fish per gill net) and trap net (0.4 to 0.5 fish per trap net) catch rates for lake class 24. Gill nets and standard survey trap nets are ineffective at sampling larger muskellunge. The lengths of the 5 fish caught in gill nets and trap nets ranged from 33.1 to 45.1 inches with an average of 40.4 inches. Therefore, large frame trap nets are used in the spring months (April and May) to assess the Fox Lake muskellunge population. In 2009, a large frame trap net survey was conducted for the first time; 95 muskellunge were sampled. The muskellunge ranged in length from 33.0 to 48.2 inches with an average of 40.7 inches. In 2009, 33% of the muskellunge sampled were greater than 42 inches. A follow-up large frame trap net survey was conducted in the spring of 2011, which is the start of a long-term monitoring study to obtain a population estimate. In 2011, 140 muskellunge were caught over 2 weeks in May. The muskellunge ranged in length from 14.5 to 48.9 inches with an average length of 41.7 inches. In 2011, 45% of the muskellunge sampled were greater than 42 inches. The chance of producing a very large muskellunge is excellent in Fox Lake creating a unique experience in southern Minnesota.


The crappie population abundance is down from our long term catch rate average. The crappie catch rates during 2011 were 2.5 fish per trap net (black crappie) and 1.7 fish per trap net (white crappie). Both black and white crappie trap net catches were within their normal ranges of 1.8 to 21.2 fish per trap net and 0.5 to 6.6 fish per trap net respectively. From the late 1990's until the mid 2000's Fox Lake experienced high catch rates of both black and white crappie that were routinely near or above the upper quartile range for each species. While the catch rates were high from the late 1990's until the mid 2000's, the average weight per fish never exceeded one-third of a pound. Currently, the black and white crappie populations have very high average weights at 0.7 and 0.6 pounds, respectively, even though the population abundance has taken a hit. Total lengths of black crappie ranged from 6.6 to 14.8 inches with a mean of 10.3 inches. Total lengths of white crappie ranged from 3.9 to 11.9 inches with a mean of 9.7 inches. The size of fish in the gill net and trap net sample indicated the crappie populations are both dominated by large fish (10 inches or greater). With a large size and a lower abundance compared to previous surveys, the overall conditions of black and white crappie were good. This suggested that both crappie populations were foraging successfully.


Black bullhead have experienced a decline in abundance in Fox Lake since the early 1990's. In 2010, the catch rate was less than 1 fish per net for both gill nets (0.7) and trap nets (0.5). All black bullhead caught (n=10) were greater than 7 inches with one fish greater than 12 inches indicating a population that is experiencing poor recruitment as a result of reproduction failure or high predation on young fish. In 2011, no black bullhead were caught in gill nets or trap nets adding to the credibility of recruitment failure in Fox Lake. Local reports observe schools of Age 0 black bullhead on the surface in the spring, but they most likely end up as forage for predators.


Common carp abundance has declined in both trap nets and gill nets since 2003. However common carp catch rates have increased since 2010. In 2011, the gill net catch rate was 2.7 per net which is within the normal range of 0.3 to 3.0. The trap net catch rate was 1.2 which was also within the normal range of 0.4 to 2.0 fish per net. The spike in catch rates in gill nets and trap nets appears to be the result of one year class (Age 1 fish). Eighty-seven percent of the fish were 13-19 inches. It would appear that a successful year class was produced despite the lack of winterkill that is thought to trigger common carp natural reproduction.


The yellow perch catch rate in 2010 was 1.8 fish per gill net and was less than the normal range of 2.0 to 27.9 fish per gill net for lake class 24. This is perplexing because the 2010 catch rate was the second highest observed (44.0 per gill net) since sampling began in 1981. The 2011 trap net catch rate was 0.8, which was within the normal range of 0.3 to 1.7 fish per gill net. It is obvious that the yellow perch population is suppressed most likely due to their prey status with walleye and muskellunge present in the lake. The total lengths of yellow perch ranged from 6.4 to 9.2 inches with a mean of 7.9 inches. The gill net and trap net sample indicated a balanced size structure. The overall condition of the yellow perch was fair and indicated the fish were foraging adequately. The yellow perch population appears to be suppressed but maintaining a balanced size structure including spawning stock to reproduce in the future.


Other species sampled in gill nets and trap nets were bigmouth buffalo, bluegill, common carp, channel catfish, freshwater drum, golden shiner, hybrid sunfish, largemouth bass and quillback carpsucker. All species listed above were within or near their respected normal ranges except for freshwater drum, which had a catch rate greater than normal. The freshwater drum catch rate was 35.0 fish per gill net. According to our historical netting information from Fox Lake, the average catch rate in gill nets is 42.3 fish per gill net. The last 4 years catch rates have stabilized around 35 to 38 fish per gill net. The average total length of freshwater drum captured has increased in gill nets and trap nets since 2004. It is possible that predators are cropping off the smaller fish as forage. Freshwater drum could be forage for crappie, muskellunge, yellow perch, and walleye. Additionally, the overall condition for all of the species listed above were good, indicating populations that are not experiencing foraging stress.


The Fox Lake fish community appears to be healthy and abundance of primary management species is within normal ranges or higher. Further Improvements in the lake for the fish community should focus on best management practices in the watershed. Improvements and education in land stewardship will often have secondary benefits to the lake in the way of quality and quantity of habitat. Generally, improvements in the quality and quantity of lake habitat will result in direct improvements for the fish community.

INTRODUCTION

Fox Lake is a 1,041acre lake located in south-central Minnesota near the city of Sherburn in Martin County. Fox Lake has a maximum depth of 20 feet but 75 percent of the lake has water less than15 feet deep. Minnesota lakes managed for fishing are grouped into classes based on physical and chemical similarities and Fox Lake is assigned to lake class 24. Lake class 24 consists of shallower, relatively turbid (brown colored water) lakes high in nutrients that have some shallow water areas and are irregularly shaped (not round). The lake-to-watershed ratio for Fox Lake is 4-to-1, which indicates a small influence of the watershed to the lake. Recent watershed improvements have led to the return of aquatic vegetation in Fox Lake. Water clarity is improving, a 2.6 foot water transparency was observed during the summer of 2013. A Martin County Soil and Watershed District led program started in 2012 is focused on further improving watershed conditions for Fox Lake as well other Martin County Lakes. Improvements in the watershed for Fox Lake will continue to manifest in improved water quality and thereby improved habitat conditions for the fish community.

Like many lakes in southern Minnesota, Fox Lake is managed for walleye and crappie. However, Fox Lake is unique to the Windom Fish management area because it is managed for muskie and it is the southernmost muskie lake in the state, which provides a very unique angling opportunity. In addition, the fish population of Fox Lake has been surveyed by DNR annually since 1991, which has provided an exceptional dataset to understand the fish community with a better ability to focus fish management decisions. Finally, unlike many lakes in southern Minnesota, Fox Lake has never been aerated during the winter and provides a more stable dissolved oxygen profile during winter when compared to other area lakes. Ultimately, Fox Lake has proven to be a valuable and unique resource in southern Minnesota for lakeshore owners, local and regional anglers, as well as general recreational users.

A fish population assessment is conducted each September. The following information outlines the information collected during the latest population assessment in September 2013 using 11 trap nets and 6 gill nets.


WALLEYE

The expected gill net catch rate of walleye in Fox Lake is between 1.2 and 6.3 per net and the expected range for the trap net catch rate is between 0.3 and 1.2 per net. The gill net catch rate in 2013 was 1.8 per net which is within the expected range, but less than desired for Fox Lake based on the lake management plan. The trap net catch rate was only less than 0.1 per net, which was below the interquartile range for Fox Lake. Historically, the Fox Lake gill net catch rate has been sporadic with catches ranging from 0.5 to 45.2 from 1981 to 2001 with an average catch rate of 9.8 per gill net during that same time frame. Since 2002, the catch rates have varied to a lesser degree from 0.5 to 4.0 with an average catch rate of 2.4 walleye per gill net indicating a more stable walleye population. The reduction in the average catch rate from 9.8 walleye per gill net from 1981 to 2001 to 2.4 walleye per gill net from 2002 to 2013 is not easily explainable and is most likely the result of many factors. From 1979 to 2009 Fox Lake has been stocked with walleye fry, fingerlings, yearlings, and adults depending on production. When the catch rate after stocking was analyzed, the highest catch rates were associated with fry stockings in 1983 and 1984 and intensive fingerling stocking in 1992 and 1993. But, suppressed catch rates were also associated with fry and fingerling stocking from 2002 to 2013 indicating other factors may be involved. Since 1998, competition for limited prey resources has never been higher in Fox Lake with the emergence of robust populations of white crappie, black crappie, channel catfish and the decline of black bullhead as a forage base. In addition, muskie have been stocked in Fox Lake starting in 1999 adding an additional predator to compete with for limited prey items (yellow perch, small common carp, small freshwater drum, and seasonally abundant minnow species). Starting in 2010, walleye frylings (2 to 3 inch fish) have been stocked annually (except 2012 when production failed) which led to a slight improvement in gill net catch rates to 3.2 to 3.5 fish per gill net from 2011 to 2012. Given only a slight improvement, competition with other predators appears to continue to suppress the walleye population abundance. In 2013, fingerling walleye were stocked in the fall in addition to frylings in the spring. Monitoring of the walleye population in 2014 will indicate if that stocking was successful. While the catch rates have been suppressed in recent years, the size structure of the population does appear to be improving. The number of 15 inch and larger walleye is increasing. Larger fish are becoming more common and local anglers have even stated that the walleye fishing is the "best walleye fishing in recent years". The walleye in the 2013 sample ranged from 14.8 to 19.5 inches with an average size of 17.7 inches. Additionally, the walleye in the sample were healthy with an average weight above 2 pounds. Future abundance of the walleye population appears directly related to other species given the competition for limited food sources. Improvement of the walleye population abundance will most likely occur if other predator species abundance decreases (crappies, channel catfish, muskie, or largemouth bass). The population appears to be at a level that provides some good fishing opportunities, but less than a population level that makes walleyes the dominant game species in the lake.


MUSKIE

Muskie have been stocked into Fox Lake starting in 1999 with subsequent stockings in 2001, 2004, 2006, 2008, 2010, and 2012. No natural reproduction of muskie has been documented in Fox Lake so all muskie in the lake are from stocking. Year classes present from the stockings are ages 1, 4, 5, 7, 9, 12, and 16. Muskies over 10 years old have the ability to reach trophy size so potential exists for the Fox Lake muskie population to have trophy individuals present in the lake. In 2013, 2 muskies were caught in the gill net sample (a little more than 0.3 fish per net). Muskie are not effectively sampled with gill nets and standard trap nets and the long-term catch rates from 2000 to 2013 reflect that with gill net catch rates varying from only 0 to 0.7 fish per net. Therefore, in 2011 a long-term muskie study was started focusing on obtaining information leading to a population estimate that will help determine the ideal stocking rate for Fox Lake. Large-frame trap nets were used in 2011, 2012, and 2013 in the spring to capture muskie, particularly muskie greater than 34 inches and thus considered mature. In 2011, 140 muskie were caught over 2 weeks in May. The muskie ranged in length from 14.5 to 48.9 inches with an average length of 41.7 inches. In 2012, 45 muskie were caught over 3 weeks in April and May. The muskie ranged in length from 31.0 to 48.7 inches with an average length of 41.5 inches. In 2013, 107 muskie were sampled over 2 weeks in April and May. The muskie ranged in length from 29.0 to 50.4 inches with an average length of 41.1 inches. The population estimate of muskie greater than 34 inches ranges anywhere from 190 to 287 fish with 95% confidence. This indicates the population is doing well and many large muskies are present in the lake. The muskie population will be monitored every other year with large frame trap nets starting in 2015.


CRAPPIE

Two species of crappie are present in Fox Lake, black crappie and white crappie. The catch rates of black crappie were 5.7 fish per gill net and 5.4 fish per trap net and the catch rates of white crappie were 0.3 fish per trap net with no white crappie in the gill net sample. Catch rates of crappie are not necessarily the best indicator of how well the population is doing. Crappie catch rates tend to vary widely from year to year and even from season to season and the population size structure is more indicative of the overall health of the population in the lake. Black crappie ranged in size from 3.2 to 12.7 inches with an average length of 7.3 inches in the gill net sample and 5.9 inches in the trap net sample. More than 60% of the black crappie in the sample were 10 inches or greater and about 35% were bigger than 12 inches. White crappie ranged in size from 10.75 to 11.06 inches with an average size of 10.91 inches. All white crappie in the sample were larger than 10 inches. Overall, it appears that the black and white crappie populations have an imbalanced size structure with most of the fish being larger than 8 inches. An imbalanced size structure can indicate that a year class of crappie is missing from the sample, whether from failed spawning or from bad sampling during the time period of the sample. Future assessments, including potential spring trap netting in 2014 when they are moving near shore, will monitor the black crappie populations to determine if they are truly out of balance or if they were ineffectively sampled in 2013.


YELLOW PERCH

Yellow perch in Fox Lake are the main forage for the walleye and muskie populations. Fluctuations in the abundance of the yellow perch population can lead to fluctuations in the walleye and muskellunge populations. The historical catch rates of yellow perch in the gill nets range from a low of 0.3 per gill net in 1992 to a high of 80.5 in 2012 and from 0 per trap net (1986, 1989, and 1992) to 22.6 per trap net in 1997. The 2013 gill net catch rate was one of the lowest on record at 1.5 fish per gill net which is unusual because the catch rate in 2012 was the highest on record at 80.5 per gill net. A cause in the swing in catch rate from one of the greatest to one of the lowest is not completely understood at this time, but growth of large aquatic vegetation beds over the last 5 years may give the yellow perch a place to successfully hide from survey nets as well as from predators. Increased survival of the yellow perch in Fox Lake as a result of increased vegetation growth will increase the chances of sustaining a consistent abundance of forage sized fish in the lake which will help the yellow perch population sustain itself in addition to sustaining the walleye and muskellunge populations. The size of yellow perch in the 2013 sample ranged from 4.5 to 9.3 inches with an average length of 8.0 inches in the gill net sample and 6.3 inches in the trap net sample. This range of sizes should be adequate as a forage base even if perch are low in abundance. Spawning sized fish remain in the population and successful reproduction in the future may help to boost the forage base and add an additional angling opportunity.


OTHER SPECIES

Other species of fish caught in the 2013 survey were bigmouth buffalo, black bullhead, channel catfish, common carp, freshwater drum, and largemouth bass. Of the species listed above, channel catfish and freshwater drum are the most significant contributors to the fish community in terms of relative biomass (weight of fish available as a relation to the total weight of all fish species in the lake combine). Channel catfish are doing well in Fox Lake and currently range in length from 22.1 to 26.4 inches with an average weight of 5.1 pounds. The abundant channel catfish population is the suspected reason why the bullhead population is not as prevalent as it has been in the past due to predation and competition for common resources. Finally, freshwater drum are the most prevalent "rough" fish in the population with a gill net catch rate of 64.8 fish per net. Freshwater drum in the 2013 sample ranged in length from 3.8 to 18.0 inches with an average of 10.9 inches in the gill net sample and 13.7 inches in the trap net sample. With an abundant muskie and potentially expanding walleye population, small freshwater drum will increasingly become important as prey species for larger muskellunge and walleye.


SUMMARY

Overall, the Fox Lake fish community appears to be doing well with a diverse fish community that is seeing improvements in managed fish species abundance and/or size structure. Further Improvements in the lake for the fish community should focus on best management practices in the watershed. Improvements and education in land stewardship will often have secondary benefits to the lake in the way of quality and quantity of habitat. Generally, improvements in the quality and quantity of lake habitat will result in direct improvements for the fish community. Wise use of our resources makes us good stewards to the land and water that all of us use every day.

Fox Lake is a 1,041-acre lake located in Martin County near the City of Sherburn. Fox Lake has a maximum depth of 20 feet and is not aerated. Fox Lake's watershed is relatively small indicating a potentially small impact from its surrounding landscape. Watershed improvements and the closing of a diversion structure have created a better opportunity for the return of aquatic vegetation, which provides habitat for several species of fish. In addition, curly-leaf pondweed can become abundant in the southeast area of Fox Lake when conditions are favorable. Curly-leaf Pondweed was first documented during a survey in 2006. Fox Lake provides a unique fishery, it is managed primarily for Muskellunge and Walleye and secondarily for crappie, making it one of two lakes in the Windom fisheries management area that provide Muskellunge angling opportunities. A rarity in the Windom Fish Management Area is annual surveying of a lake, however, Fox has an annual survey conducted during the first week of September to monitor fish populations using six gill nets and 12 trap nets.

WALLEYE
In 2019, the Walleye catch rate was 1.7 per gill net, which is within the expected range of catch rates for similar lakes (1.2 to 6.3 per gill net). From 2015 to 2017 the Fox Lake Walleye catch rate was on a 3 year increasing trend (5.7 in 2015, 9.8 in 2016, and 14.5 in 2017). However, the past 2 years the gill net catch has been very low. Interestingly, trap net catch rates during those 2 years has been decent with a catch rate of 1.0 in 2018 and 1.42 in 2019. It appears during the week of sampling in 2019 Walleye may have remained near shore away from the gill nets. Gill nets are an offshore sampling method and capture fish in deeper water. Lengths of Walleye ranged from just under 8 inches to just over 27.5 inches and averaged 13 inches in gill nets and 15.5 inches in trap nets. Unfortunately, Walleyes in the sample were in below average health. Fox Lake Walleye appear to be experiencing some stress based on how plump the fish appear. Due to low catch rates of Walleye over the past 2 years with fish in poor health, stocking of Walleye fry will occur when surplus Walleye are produced in the hatchery. Surplus Walleye fry were produced in 2019 and were stocked into Fox Lake. The Walleye population will continue to be monitored annually to maintain an opportunity for Walleye fishing in Fox Lake.

MUSKELLUNGE
Muskellunge were first introduced into Fox Lake in 1999. Subsequently they were stocked in 2001 and were stocked every other year from 2004 to 2018. However due to production constraints, starting in 2019, Muskellunge were stocked and will continue to be stocked every-other year (odd year stocking). Four Muskellunge were captured in trap nets in the annual standard survey. Gill nets and trap nets are usually ineffective at sampling Muskellunge. The 4 fish ranged in length from 35.0 to 41.5 inches with an average length of 38.3 inches. In the 2017 assessment using large frame trap nets, Muskellunge were captured at a rate of 3.9 per net per day. Muskellunge ranged in length from 10.8 to 50.1 inches and averaged 42.2 inches. The population estimate in 2016 (the last reliable estimate) was 241 adults (192 to 290). Since 2011, 325 unique adult Muskellunge have been sampled and PIT (Passive Integrated Transponder-a unique identifier) tagged and 2,474 fingerling Muskie have been PIT tagged and stocked.

CRAPPIE
In 2019, Black Crappie were captured at a rate of 52.5 per trap net, which is more than the expected range of catch rates for similar lakes (1.8 to 21.2 per trap net) and the second highest ever recorded. Additionally, the catch rate is greater than the long-term average of nearly 15.7 per trap net since 1981. Fox Lake has had 5 years in a row of catch rates above the long-term average indicating a return of good numbers of crappie. Lengths of Black Crappie ranged from under 3 inches to just shy of 10 inches in gill nets and trap nets and averaged nearly 7.5 inches in trap nets. The average length is similar to 2018 indicating slower growth. Black Crappie are feeding successfully as indicated by how plump the fish are. The Black Crappie population is self-sustaining and stable with at least 2 or 3 strong year classes present based on length frequency in trap nets.

The White Crappie catch rate in 2019 was 5.3 per trap net, which is within the expected range of catch rates for similar lakes (0.5 to 6.6). White Crappie lengths ranged from just over 5 inches to just above 12.5 inches and averaged 7.5 inches in the trap net sample. Although the two species of crappie can coexist, Black Crappie are dominating the Fox Lake crappie fishery. However, it appears that the larger fish, over 10 inches, in the crappie population are White Crappie.

Angling for Black or White Crappie should be good over the next 5 to 6 years. There appears to be enough food to support the populations as they were healthy fish in good condition. Multiple strong year classes are present and the fish, although slow growing, should attain 10 inches or greater over the next several years.

OTHER SPECIES
The Yellow Perch catch rate in 2019 was 0.3 per gill net, which is less than the expected range of catch rates for similar lakes (2.0 to 27.9 per gill net). The catch rate of Yellow Perch has been characterized by extreme ups and downs since 2011. The gill net catch rate was 1.8 in 2011, then 80.5 in 2012 and back to 1.5 in 2013 followed by 25, 27.7, and 30.5 from 2014 to 2017 and most recently down to 0.5 and 0.3 in 2018 and 2019. Yellow Perch naturally reproduce as the variability in catches is not a byproduct of stocking. This variability in gill net catch is most likely due to environmental conditions and not true population changes. However, if the population remains low in 2020 there may be a need to restock to boost the population. Lengths of Yellow Perch ranged from just under 6 inches to 8.5 inches and averaged just shy of 7 inches in gill nets and just over 7 inches in trap nets.

The Freshwater Drum catch rate was 45.3 per gill net, just above the long term average of 45.2 per gill net and higher than the expected range of catch rates for similar lakes (4.0 to 32.3 per gill net). There is some desire to remove Freshwater Drum to reduce numbers, however, past studies have shown that this only leads to a reproduction response and actually speeds up growth and reproduction in Freshwater Drum. Control of Freshwater Drum will instead focus on competition and predation.

The Channel Catfish catch rate was 1.2 per gill net. Nine Channel Catfish were caught that ranged from 14.8 inches and 28.7 inches. Interestingly, we have only sampled 22 Black Bullheads in trap nets or gill nets combined since 2010 during annual netting on Fox Lake. While this number is extremely low, it is a trend that we have been observing in other lakes in the Windom Fish Management Area as well.

Thirty-five Bluegill, 3.3 to 7.9 inches in length, were sampled in trap nets. The Bluegill population is starting to become more abundant on Fox Lake. There could be a shift in habitat that favors Bluegill and crappie over Yellow Perch.

Other species sampled included Bigmouth Buffalo, Common Carp, Golden Shiner, Hybrid Sunfish, Largemouth Bass, and Quillback Carpsucker.

Muskie were first introduced into Fox Lake in 1999 and subsequently stocked in 2001 and have been stocked every other year from 2004 to 2018. The last two stockings were in October 2019 (N=475) and October 2022 (N=476). The recent 3 year gap in stocking was a byproduct of inconsistent statewide Muskie production, COVID related cessation of stocking in 2020, and a statewide reprioritization along with improvement in lessons learned with Muskie management. No Muskie were captured in gill nets or trap nets in the 2022 survey. Gill nets and trap nets are usually ineffective at sampling Muskie during our annual survey in September. Therefore, large frame trap nets are set every 5 years to sample the Muskie population. A survey utilizing the large frame trap nets was done in May 2022. No Muskies were sampled. Five years prior during the 2017 assessment Muskie were captured at a rate of 3.9 per net per day. During 2017, Muskie ranged in length from 10.8 to 50.1 inches and averaged 42.2 inches. The population estimate in 2016 (the last reliable estimate using 2017 as a recapture event) was 250 adults (193 to 307; 95 Percent Confidence Interval). Given the recent water quality issues, however, a special targeted LTN assessment was conducted during the spring of 2021. Five Muskie were caught in 3 days of netting with 2 nets each day (6 net nights). Muskies sampled ranged in length from 39.1 to 48.9 inches with an average length of 42.2 inches. Three males and 2 females were sampled. Therefore, it is strange that 0 Muskie were sampled in 2022. We suspect that the adult Muskie population has shifted to a much less abundant population, but Muskies are most likely still present. It is very likely that the originally stocked fish in 1999 and the following year class in 2001 are now gone from the lake due to old age. Since 2011 when PIT tagging was started on Fox Lake, 325 unique adult Muskie have been sampled and PIT tagged and 2,950 fingerling Muskie have been PIT tagged and stocked.
