Fox Lake is a unique system in the pothole prairie region because of the lake's physical characteristics. Fox Lake is one of the deeper lakes in this area and the orientation of the lake is mostly east and west. Fox Lake is the only lake managed by the Windom office that has been sampled on a yearly basis since 1991. This unique sampling situation enables the Windom Office to follow the fish population trends and thus increases the effectiveness of evaluating and managing the populations. Additionally, Fox Lake is the only lake in this area that is managed secondarily for muskellunge. Approximately 520 muskellunge (Age 2+) were stocked in the fall of 1999 after a public comment period. The general public had overwhelming support of the concept so muskellunge (1-2 pounds/fish) were stocked. The following information was collected before muskellunge were stocked so no effect of this species was observed in these data. The average walleye gill net catch was 3.13 fish/net set which was within the normal range for this type of lake. Despite the walleye catch rates being normal compared to other area lakes, only one other time in the last 10 consecutive surveys (1987) has catch rates been so low. The average walleye gill net sample weight however, was the highest (2.37 lbs./fish) in the last ten consecutive surveys. Total lengths of walleye sampled in our gill nets ranged from 9.9 to 25.9 inches and had a mean of 18.5. Many walleye were 17 to 18 inches in length, which would make these fish 3 or 4 years old. All of this means that walleye numbers may be lower than in the past but the average is larger. Fall electrofishing for young of the year walleye indicated some natural reproduction and/or fry survival in 1999 (23 young of the year walleye/hour). These data are important because historical fall electrofishing and shoreline seining indicate very limited natural reproduction. Another year class of walleye recruiting to the population is highly possible if survival is good for the young of the year walleye sampled in the fall. Survival of young of the year walleye would probably be improved if aquatic vegetation could be abundant. Aquatic vegetation, acting as nursery habitat, enables smaller walleye and other forage fish to escape from larger predators. The current Fox Lake walleye stocking regime calls for fry three out of four years at a rate of 1000 per surface acre. Crappie population densities are susceptible to extreme fluctuations in the pothole prairie region. Examining the historical catches from Fox Lake, it appears both black and white crappie populations are in or nearing a high point in the cycle. Based on trap netting, the black crappie population is looking quite promising for anglers. The average black crappie trap net catch was 13.08 fish/net which was higher than normal for this type of lake. Historically, average black crappie trap net catches have been higher during two other periods (1998, 1995) in the last nine consecutive surveys. Total lengths of black crappie sampled in our trap nets ranged between 4.2 and 8.4 inches, with a mean of 7.0. A mode was recorded in the range of 6.5 to 7.0 inches. Overall the last few years the white crappie population has becom more abundant than the black crappie population. Fisheries literature indicates that white crappies tend to survive better in more turbid environments (less transparent water). The average white crappie trap net catch was 53.17 fish/net set which was eight times higher than normal for this lake type. Total lengths of white crappie sampled in trap nets ranged between 6.1 and 9.8 inches, with a mean of 7.3. Since 1997, the average white crappie trap net catches have been steadily increasing. All of these data suggest the white crappie population is relatively dense and consists mostly of smaller individuals. Fishing for both white and black crappie could be phenomenal for the next couple of years.Bluegill and largemouth bass usually do considerably better when aquatic vegetation is abundant. The average bluegill trap net catch was 2.0 fish/net set which was below normal for this lake type. However, the average bluegill trap net catches have been above normal only once in the last nine consecutive surveys. Total lengths of bluegill sampled in trap nets ranged between 3.8 and 7.3 inches, with a mean of 6.3. Historical shoreline seining has revealed varying numbers of young of the year bluegill which suggests some natural reproduction. These data suggest the bluegill population is self-sustaining but at a low density. Aquatic vegetation would likely enhance this population. The average channel catfish gill net catch was 7.50 fish/net set which was the second highest catch in the last 10 consecutive surveys. The highest catch was 7.83 fish/net set in 1997. Total lengths of channel catfish sampled in our gill nets ranged between 11.5 and 21.3 inches, with a mean of 14.5. Nearly 76% of the channel catfish aged were 5 years old (average length= 14.8 inches) while the remaining were Age 4 (average length=12.5 inches). Channel catfish were last stocked in 1986 which indicates the population was basically self-sustaining. Freshwater drum, black bullhead and common carp populations in Fox Lake could provide the opportunity to teach some kids how to fish. The freshwater drum population was doing quite well in spite of a moderate "summerkill" in 1999. The average gill net catch was 45.13 fish/net set which was above normal. Based on the last ten consecutive surveys, the average freshwater drum gill net catches have only twice been lower than normal. Total lengths of freshwater drum sampled in the gill nets ranged between 4.6 and 9.7 inches, with a mean of 8.2. These data suggest the freshwater drum population density was relatively high and consisted mostly of smaller individuals. The average black bullhead gill net catch was 27.88 fish/net set which was higher than normal for this type of lake. Total lengths of black bullhead ranged between 7.7 and 10.6 inches, with a mean of 8.8. These data suggest a normal to above normal black bullhead density and a population size structure that consisted mostly of smaller individuals. The average common carp trap net catch was 3.17 fish/net set which was higher than normal for this type of lake. Total lengths of common carp sampled in the trap nets ranged between 16.7 and 32.3 inches, with a mean of 25.5. Fox Lake has a common carp population density that was relatively low and a size structure that consisted mostly of larger individuals. To promote and maintain healthy fish populations, pollution and other inputs need to be controlled. Fish habitats are directly affected by water quality. Nutrient, sediment and other waste inputs can drastically alter the biological, chemical, and physical components of a lake. It is paramount to maintain if not improve the current water quality of Fox Lake through watershed management to preserve this fishery for future generations to enjoy.

Fox Lake, near the town of Sherburn in Martin County, has a maximum of 20 feet deep and encompasses 1041 acres. It is managed primarily for walleye and muskellunge. Additionally, Fox Lake is managed secondarily for black and white crappie and channel catfish. The current walleye stocking regime calls for fingerling stocking at a pound per acre every other year (2001 and 2003). The 2001 walleye fingerling stocking consisted of approximately 1500 pounds of fingerlings (76,511 fish) in an effort to boost the walleye fishery. The last muskellunge fingerlings (yearlings) are scheduled to be stocked in the fall of 2003 after which the muskellunge stocking will be evaluated. Five gill net sets and 11 trap net sets were used to assess the Fox Lake fishery during the week of September 9, 2002. The walleye catch rate in gill nets averaged 1.20/set which was just barely within the expected range. They averaged 18.2 inches in length. The walleye stocking regime was changed to stocking fingerlings because walleye catch rates have been less than usual since 1999. Despite the fact that gill nets sampled fewer walleyes, trap net catch rates remained nearly identical to the last three surveys. Six different year classes of walleyes were captured and indicated growth was quite good as Age 1 walleye averaged 10.79 inches while Age 2 walleye were 16.20 inches. Creel surveys indicated that 45 percent of all anglers interviewed were seeking walleye. It is somewhat interesting that boat anglers experienced lower walleye catch rates than bank anglers. Based on the creel data it would appear that bank angling would actually improve your walleye catch rates. The moral of the story is the walleye numbers remain low but crappie and channel catfish numbers are quite high. Four muskellunge were captured in trap nets during the survey in 2002 and in 2001. Two of the fish from the 2002 survey were from the 1999 stocking and the other two were from the 2001 stocking. The fish from the 1999 stocking were around 32 inches while the fish from the 2001 stocking were around 16 inches. All of the fish appeared to be in good condition and doing well. Remember it is unlawful to possess a muskellunge that is less than 40 inches in length. Give these fish a chance to become established, so practice catch and release.The black crappie catch rate in trap nets was 25.64/set and averaged 6.11 inches. Four year classes of black crappie were captured, with the 2001 year class (91% of the black crappie) the most abundant. The white crappie catch rate in trap nets was 43.00/set and averaged 6.91 inches in length. Eighty-two percent of the white crappie caught were from the 2001 year class. Fox Lake over the years has maintained relatively high abundances of both black and white crappie, which is unique as panfish populations tend to cycle in the pothole prairie lakes of southern Minnesota. Give these fish a few years to grow and they will provide some excellent fishing if you can find them.The channel catfish catch rate was 15.20/set in gill nets and 2.45/set in trap nets, which was the highest catch rate in either gear ever captured in all the years of surveying Fox Lake. Total lengths of channel catfish captured averaged 12.81 inches and ranged from 7.28 to 22.83 inches. Despite not being stocked since 1986, the channel catfish population has been self-sufficient and it appears that in 2000, 1996, and 1995 year classes were successfully produced. A total of fourteen species of fish were captured during the survey of 2002. Other species captured were yellow perch, northern pike, common carp, black bullhead, bigmouth buffalo, bluegill, white sucker, and yellow bullhead.To promote and maintain healthy fish populations, pollution and other inputs need to be controlled. Fish habitats are directly affected by water quality. Nutrient, sediment and other waste inputs can drastically alter the biological, chemical, and physical components of a lake. It is paramount to maintain if not improve the current water quality of Fox Lake through watershed management to preserve this fishery for future generations to enjoy. Prepared by Ryan Doorenbos

Fox Lake, near the town of Sherburn, is a 1,041-acre lake with a maximum depth of 18 feet. Fox Lake has a low watershed to lake ratio of 4 to 1, which indicates a smaller drainage area when compared to the surface acres of the lake. Fox Lake is managed primarily for walleye and muskellunge and secondarily for channel catfish, white crappie, and black crappie. The annual population assessment was conducted during the week of September 2, 2008.

Historically, walleye catch rates have not changed much in over 8 years despite regular walleye fingerling stockings. The regular stockings were equivalent to stocking 20 walleye fingerlings/acre/year with little return to the survey. Total lengths of walleye sampled ranged from 8.4 to 26.4 inches and averaged 16.8 inches. Six year classes of walleye were sampled in 2008 with most correlating back to fingerling stockings in 2004, 2005, and 2006. Nearly half the walleye sampled in 2008 were 14 inches and larger. Although numbers were higher in the early 90s, walleye can still be caught with regularity as reported in the open water creel survey on Fox Lake in 2008.

A total of 4 muskellunge were sampled in trap nets and gill nets combined in 2008. Muskellunge sampling has been extremely challenging over the years. Typically we sample very few muskies each year during the annual assessment. In the last 8 assessments we have sampled a total of 26 muskies in trap nets and gill nets combined. Although muskie sampling can be difficult and sample sizes are typically small, the sizes of fish captured indicate the presence of legal sized fish. The creel survey during the open water period of 2008 showed that 25% of the anglers fishing Fox Lake were targeting muskellunge. The creel survey estimated that 203 muskellunge were captured and only 8 were harvested. Nearly 96% of the muskellunge captured were released. The estimated average size muskie caught was just over 37 inches. Muskellunge (520 fish) will continue to be stocked in even years through 2010. In the spring of 2009, we are planning to conduct another special assessment to get better estimates of muskie size structure and abundance.

The channel catfish catch rate in gill nets was 4.5 fish/set, which was down from the 2007 assessment of 11.3 fish/set. Historically catch rates have ranged from 0.6 to 15.2 fish/set. Total lengths of channel catfish ranged from 18.6 to 25.4 inches with a mean of 21.4 inches. The average total length channel catfish sampled in gill nets has increased 8.6 inches during a 6-year time frame. During a mid-summer evening, there is a good chance of catching some nice sized channel catfish.

The black crappie catch rate in trap nets was 5.4 fish/set, which was within the expected range (1.8 to 21.2 fish/set). Based on trap net catch rates, black crappie numbers have not changed since last year. Total lengths of black crappie in trap nets ranged from 3.2 to 11.8 inches and averaged 9.3 inches. It would appear that white crappie outnumber black crappie in Fox Lake by at least 2 to 1. Total lengths and average sizes are similar between the two species. Either species can provide some good action. Since 2004, both species have showed an increase of 2 inches in average length.

Compared to last year, yellow perch numbers are nearly the same. Total lengths ranged from 6.5 to 8.9 inches and averaged 7.4 inches. Most of the fish sampled were in the 6.5 to 8.0 inch range. It is possible to catch a few perch while targeting the seemingly abundant crappie in Fox Lake.

Freshwater drum, or sheephead, numbers continue to be relatively high. Since 1981, sheephead numbers continue to be nearly the same but average size is increasing. This may suggest that predators, such as walleyes or muskellunge, are foraging on the smaller freshwater drum and thereby shifting the size structure toward larger fish. Total lengths ranged from 11.0 to 19.1 inches and averaged 12.9 inches.

Black bullhead numbers in Fox Lake continue to decline. A total of 10 black bullhead were sampled in gill nets and trap nets combined in 2008. Since 1999, catch rates during annual assessments have revealed a declining trend in abundance. However, all of the bullheads sampled in 2008 were at least 10 inches in total length. Natural reproduction is either very limited and/or heavy predation on smaller bullheads limit their abundance. It is possible to catch a bullhead on Fox Lake but there are plenty of lakes nearby with better abundance, such as Big Twin Lake.

Other species captured were bigmouth buffalo, bluegill, common carp, golden shiner, largemouth bass, and yellow bullhead.

Efforts to improve the health of the lake should focus on best management practices within the watershed. Improvements and education in land stewardship will often have secondary benefits to the lake in the way of quality and quantity of habitat. Generally, improvements in the quality and quantity of lake habitat will mean direct improvements of the fishery.

Prepared by Ryan Doorenbos

Fox Lake, near the town of Sherburn, is a 1,041-acre lake in Martin County with a maximum depth of 20 feet. In the last few years aquatic vegetation (mostly sago pondweed and claspingleaf pondweed) has gradually increased in abundance. Unfortunately curlyleaf pondweed (exotic species) was documented in Fox Lake as well. The Windom Area Office will be adding an additional vegetation survey to monitor this exotic species. Generally when we see increasing aquatic vegetation in an area lake, it is a result of increasing water clarity. Sago pondweed is important for fish and wildlife as it provides nursery and feeding habitat for small fish as well as cover from predators. Sago pondweed is also valuable from the water quality standpoint as nutrients are tied up in the aquatic vegetation instead of being available for algae production. Fox Lake is managed primarily for walleye and muskellunge and secondarily for black crappie, white crappie, and bluegill. A population assessment was conducted during the week of September 8, 2009 using gillnets and trap nets.

The gillnet catch of walleye in 2009 was a little over one fish/net, but within the objective range. However, the catch of walleye fell short of the long range goal of 6 fish/net. Although walleye catch has averaged 6.7 fish/net historically in Fox Lake dating back to 1981, the long range goal for walleye catch in Fox Lake has been achieved only 9 times out of 24 assessments and only once in the past 11 years. This has been the case even though walleye stockings have equaled 20 fingerlings/acre/year. Since 2001 the walleye gillnet catch rate has not changed substantially and indicates a walleye population with low numbers despite an aggressive annual stocking of fingerlings. Although numbers of walleye were low, the sizes of fish were good with walleye ranging from 10 to 26 inches and averaging 14.0 inches in length. The majority of the walleye captured represented the 2007 fingerling stocking.

Sampling muskellunge has not been effective on Fox Lake in the past number of years. For example, in the last 9 population assessments on Fox Lake a total of only 30 muskellunge were captured. During the spring of 2007, a special assessment designed to target muskellunge was conducted during early spring; however, during a 10-day period of netting only 3 muskellunge were captured. In 2009, a special assessment was repeated with larger standardized muskellunge nets for the first time and met with good results. A total of 95 muskellunge were captured and lengths of fish ranged from 33 to 48 inches with a mean around 41 inches. Overall, the muskellunge population is healthy, maturing, and continues to provide an exceptional opportunity for area/regional anglers.

The crappie population continues to do quite well in Fox Lake, with white crappies out numbering black crappies. Both black and white crappie numbers continue to be higher than anticipated in Fox Lake. Both species average lengths were nearly 10 inches with the largest crappie in the 13 inch range. Since 1994 the white crappie catch in trap nets has outnumbered the black crappie catch by 2 or even 3 to 1. Most likely, both black and white crappie have similar life histories within Fox Lake and their coexistence and hybridization has resulted in behaving as one population and not as separate populations. Coincidentally, the crappie population as a whole has demonstrated a consistent decline in abundance each year since 2002. Crappie are known to have a cyclic life-cycle, meaning that the population numbers increase during periods of good reproduction, then as the number decline due to natural and hooking mortality (removal by anglers), the sizes increase until the next round of good reproduction increases abundances again. Both black and white crappie continue to provide the best chance to catch fish in Fox Lake.


The yellow perch catch rate in gill nets was 22.7 fish/net, which was at the upper end of the expected range (2.0 to 27.9 fish/net). By comparison, the average catch rate (1981  2009) for yellow perch in gill nets in Fox Lake is 14.5 fish/set. Total lengths ranged from 6 to 10 inches and averaged about 8 inches. The chance of catching perch has been increasing since 2001 and sizes are beginning to become respectable for table fare.

The channel catfish catch rate in gill nets was 2.3 fish/net, which was down from previous years (Range-0.6 to 15.2 fish/net). Total lengths of channel catfish ranged from 17 to 25 inches with a mean of about 22 inches. During the last 7 years, the average length of channel catfish has increased by nearly 9 inches. The catch and sizes over the years suggested that channel catfish reproduction has been limited in recent years. Because walleye are a primary species of management and although there may be anglers who target channel catfish on Fox Lake during the summer months, we are not planning to stock additional channel catfish due to the possibility that they may be competing with walleye for similar resources (e.g.,, black bullhead).

Other important fish species present in Fox Lake include freshwater drum, black bullhead, common carp, and bigmouth buffalo. The catch rate for freshwater drum in gill nets was 37.3 fish/net, which exceeded the objective range (4.0 to 32.3 fish/set). In comparison, the average catch rate in gill nets since 1981 was 44.1 fish/net. There does not appear to be a trend in freshwater drum abundance. Total lengths ranged from 10 to 17 inches and averaged 12 inches. The black bullhead catch rate in gill nets was 0.2 fish/net, which was less than expected. In fact, only six black bullhead were sampled in gill nets and trap nets combined in 2009 and the population numbers have continued to decline since 1999. All of the bullheads sampled in 2009 were 11 inches and greater in length. Natural reproduction is either very limited and/or heavy predation on smaller sized bullheads limit their abundance. There are indications that common carp and bigmouth buffalo abundances are down. The 2009 gillnet catch rates of 0.0 and 0.2 for common carp and bigmouth buffalo were well below the 1981  2009 average of 6.6 and 1.3, respectively. In the last few years commercial fishing effort has declined significantly in Fox Lake due to the declining carp and buffalo numbers. Other fish species captured in relatively low abundance were bluegill, golden shiner, largemouth bass, and yellow bullhead.

Efforts to improve the health of the lake should focus on best management practices within the watershed. Improvements and education in land stewardship will often have secondary benefits to the lake in the way of quality and quantity of habitat. Generally, improvements in the quality and quantity of lake habitat will mean direct improvements of the fishery.

Prepared by Craig Soupir, NR Specialist-Fisheries

193 Muskellunge were sampled in April 2016. Nets were large frame trap nets with 100 foot leads that were set on April 25th and checked and reset in the same location each day until April 29th for a total of 4 days of sets. Of the 193 Muskellunge captured, 1 was recaptured twice and 40 were recaptured once resulting in 152 unique Muskellunge over 30" caught in 2016. Eighty of the 152 were captured for the first time ever in the 2016 netting. Each Muskellunge was tagged with a uniquely identified passive integrated transponder (PIT) tag if not tagged in a previous year. Muskellunge were tagged with PIT tags in 2011, 2012, 2013, and 2015 for a previous population estimate study so some captured muskies already had a tag.

Of the 152 unique Muskellunge that were measured there were 85 males and 61 females and 6 undetermined due to immaturity. The average length of males was 39 inches and the average length of females was 45 inches with an overall average of 42 inches. The minimum length of males was 34 inches and the minimum length of females was 39 inches. The maximum length of males was 44 inches and the maximum length of females was 51 inches. Most Muskellunge in the netting sample were over 42 inches. In addition to the good size distribution of the Muskellunge in Fox Lake, the population abundance is also good. Population estimates (# over 30 inches) have been done since 2011. The estimates range from 190 to 251. Since 2011, the population estimate has steadily increased from 190 to the current value of 251 Muskie over 30 inches in the population. This amounts to 1 Muskellunge over 30 inches for every 4 acres of water on Fox Lake. This is excellent for Fox Lake because the lake can have high densities of Freshwater Drum, Bigmouth Buffalo, and Common Carp. Those rough fish provide excellent forage and provide good food to grow the Fox Lake Muskellunge to trophy sizes.

The Muskellunge population appears to be doing well in Fox Lake with fish over 50 inches in the sample. Additional spring large netting will be conducted in 2017 to further monitor Muskellunge in Fox Lake. If anyone is interested in helping sample Muskellunge as part of the spring assessment they are welcome to contact the Windom DNR office at 507-831-2900 to volunteer.

Fox Lake is a 1,041-acre, class 24 lake located in Martin County near the City of Sherburn. Fox Lake has a maximum depth of 20 feet and is not aerated. Fox Lake's watershed is relatively small with a watershed-to-lake ratio of 4 to 1 meaning for every 4 acres of upland area there is 1 acre of water in Fox Lake. Watershed improvements and the closing of a diversion structure have resulted the return of aquatic vegetation, which provides habitat for fish. In addition, curly-leaf pondweed (an invasive plant) can become abundant in the southeast area of Fox Lake when conditions are favorable. Curly-leaf Pondweed was first documented during a survey in 2006. Fox Lake provides a unique fishery, in that it is managed primarily for Muskellunge and Walleye and secondarily for Crappie, making it one of two lakes in the Windom fisheries management area that provide Muskellunge angling opportunities. An annual survey was conducted on Fox Lake (starting September 8, 2020) to monitor fish populations using six gill nets and 12 trap nets. Since the winter of 2019, Fox Lake has experienced poor water clarity and high levels of chlorophyll a, which is indicative of an increase in nutrients leading to a persistent algae bloom. The water clarity during the netting survey was less than 1 foot. Additionally, Alkalinity was 200 part per million. For Southwest Minnesota Lakes, average alkalinity is 174 ppm with a 95% of readings falling within the 165-182 ppm range over the past 30 years. This indicates a high alkalinity level for Fox Lake. Currently, Fox Lake is experiencing nutrient overloading and resulting stress. A look at the fish community can help reveal the level of stress and potentially help pinpoint causes and solutions.

WALLEYE

In 2020, the Walleye catch rate was 0.5 per gill net, which is less than the 25 percentile (1.2 per gill net) for DNR class 24 lakes (collectively known as relatively deep southern/central Minnesota lakes). From 2015 to 2017 the Fox Lake Walleye catch rate was on a 3 year increasing trend (5.7 in 2015, 9.8 in 2016, and 14.5 in 2017). However, the past 3 years the gill net catch has been discouragingly low. However, the trap net catch rates during those 3 years has been decent with a catch rate of 1.0 in 2018, 1.42 in 2019, and 0.92 in 2020. The 2020 catch rate is within the normal range for class 24 lakes (0.27 to 1.24 per trap net). It appears during the week of sampling in 2020 Walleye may have remained near shore away from the gill nets. Gill nets are an offshore sampling method and capture fish in deeper water. Fox Lake Walleye may be experiencing stress. Three Walleye were aged and all 3 were different ages (2, 5, and 6), years when frylings (2014) and fingerlings (2015 and 2018) were stocked. An additional year class was observed in the length frequency distribution and was most likely age-1 Walleye from fry stocking in 2019 that ranged in length from 8 to 10 inches. Looking at all Walleyes sampled, lengths ranged from 8.58 to 23.66 inches and averaged 14.9 inches in gill nets and 13.6 inches in trap nets. Walleyes in the sample showed less than expected body condition and were fairly thin but this was an improvement over 2019 when many Walleye were extremely thin with large heads and skinny bodies. Due to low catch rates of Walleye over the past 3 years with fish in below average health stocking of Walleye fry will occur when surplus Walleye are produced in the hatchery. The Walleye population will continue to be monitored annually to assess the effectiveness of Walleye stocking in Fox Lake.

MUSKELLUNGE

Muskellunge were introduced into Fox Lake in 1999, were stocked in 2001 and were stocked every other year from 2004 to 2018. Starting in 2019, Muskellunge fingerlings were stocked and will continue to be stocked every-other year (a change to odd year stocking). No Muskellunge were captured in gill nets or trap nets in the 2020 survey. Gill nets and trap nets are usually ineffective at sampling Muskellunge. The last Muskellunge survey utilizing special large frame trap nets that do sample Muskellunge well was done in 2017. In the 2017 assessment Muskellunge were captured at a rate of 3.9 per net per day. Muskellunge ranged in length from 10.8 to 50.1 inches and averaged 42.2 inches. The population estimate was 241 adults at that time.

CRAPPIE

In 2020, Black Crappie were captured at a rate of 52.75 per trap net, which is greater than the 75 percentile for class 24 lakes (21.2 per trap net) and the second highest ever recorded. Additionally, the catch rate is greater than the long-term average of 16.8 per trap net since 1981. Fox Lake has had 6 successive years of catch rates above the long-term average indicating a return of good numbers of crappie. Lengths of Black Crappie ranged from 4.3 to 9.1 inches in gill nets and trap nets and averaged 6.6 inches in trap nets. The mean and maximum lengths are similar to the past several years indicating fairly slow growth. Black Crappie are self-sustaining in Fox Lake and stable with at least 2 or 3 strong year classes present based on netting.

The White Crappie catch rate in 2020 was 6 per trap net, which is within the normal range of catch rates for class 24 lakes (0.5 to 6.6 per trap net). White Crappie lengths ranged from 5.2 to 10.7 inches and averaged 7 inches in the trap net sample. Although the two species of crappie can coexist, Black Crappie are dominating the Fox Lake crappie fishery. However, it appears that the larger fish in the crappie population are White Crappie. Hybridization can happen and could lead to increased growth and maximum size of crappie in the lake. Continued monitoring will evaluate growth and hybridization.

Angling for Black or White Crappie should be good over the next several years. There appears to be enough forage to support the population as they were healthy fish in fair condition. Multiple strong year classes are present and the fish, although slow growing, should reach 10 inches or more.

OTHER SPECIES

Only 1 Yellow Perch was caught in gill nets and trap nets in 2020. The DNR may stock adult pre-spawn Yellow Perch to help boost the population.

The Freshwater Drum catch rate was 31 per gill net, within the normal range of catch rates for class 24 lakes (4.0 to 32.3 per gill net) but more than the long-term catch rate of 16 per gill net. There is some desire to remove large numbers of Freshwater Drum, however, past studies have shown that this only induces a reproduction response and can speed up growth and reproduction in Freshwater Drum. Control of Freshwater Drum will instead focus on competition and predation.

Other species sampled included Bigmouth Buffalo, Bluegill, Channel Catfish, Common Carp, Golden Shiner, and Quillback Carpsucker. Of the species listed in the previous sentence, Bigmouth Buffalo were very abundant and of particular concern. While Bigmouth Buffalo are native, they can over populate and act as a source of competition for limited food resources. They also have the ability to suspend sediments while disturbing the bottom of the lake while looking for food that can lead to internal nutrient loading and create poor water quality. Continued monitoring will be done to track changes in numbers and species caught in Fox Lake.

Fox Lake is a 1,041-acre lake with a maximum depth of 17 feet near the City of Sherburn in Martin County Minnesota. Fox Lake's upland watershed is small with only 4 acres of land for every 1 acre of water. Watershed improvements and closing of a diversion structure have facilitated the return of aquatic vegetation in some years, which provides habitat for several species of fish. In addition, curly-leaf pondweed can become abundant in the southeast area of Fox Lake when conditions are favorable. Curly-leaf Pondweed was first documented during a survey in 2006. Fox Lake provides a unique fishery, in that it is managed primarily for Muskie and Walleye and secondarily for crappie, making it one of two lakes in the Windom fisheries management area that provide Muskie angling opportunities. A survey was conducted on Fox Lake (starting September 6, 2022) to monitor fish populations using six gill nets and 11 trap nets. Surveys have been done annually since 1991 resulting in an excellent dataset to infer changes observed. While watershed improvements have been done, since the winter of 2019, Fox Lake has had poor water clarity and high levels of Chlorophyll a (greater than 100 parts per billion). The cause is not known, but high Chlorophyll a levels are indicative of an increase in nutrients (either internal or external in nature) leading to a persistent algae bloom, even under ice. Alkalinity was 220 parts per million during the survey and ranged from 163 to 169 from May to September 2022. For Southwest Minnesota Lakes, average alkalinity is 174 ppm with a 95% confidence interval of 165-182 ppm over the past 30 years. This indicates a very high alkalinity level for Fox Lake as well. Currently, Fox Lake is experiencing nutrient overloading and stress. A look at the fish community can help reveal the level of stress and potentially help pinpoint causes and solutions.

WALLEYE

Eight Walleye were caught in the trap net sample, no Walleye were caught in the gill nets. From 2015 to 2017 the Walleye catch rate was on a 3 year increasing trend (5.7 in 2015, 9.8 in 2016, and 14.5 in 2017). However, the past 5 years the gill net catch has been discouragingly low with catch rates never exceeding 1.6 per gill net. Interestingly, the trap net catch rates (# per net) during the past 5 years has been decent with 1.0 in 2018, 1.4 in 2019, 0.9 in 2020, 0.8 in 2021, and 0.7 in 2022. The 2022 trap net catch rate is within the normal range for similar lakes statewide (0.27 to 1.24 per trap net). It appears during the week of sampling in 2022 Walleye remained near shore away from the gill nets. This is typical of lakes experiencing heavy algae blooms where dissolved oxygen is low in the deep water habitat that is typically utilized during summer. All Walleye sampled in trap nets were catchable sized adults and ranged in length from 15 to 20 inches. Weights of Walleye in the sample showed an improvement compared to the past several years. Additionally, larger fish tended to maintain good plumpness indicating forage is easily available. Larger Walleye (1,422 fish at nearly 1 pound per fish, 13-15 inches) were stocked in September and October of 2021. Those stocked fish did not have to experience stressful conditions observed in Fox Lake during 2018 to 2021 and thus maintained good weight once in the lake.
Therefore, Walleye fry (390,000 fish) and fingerling (approximately 6,795 Walleye, 6-7 inches) were stocked in 2022 to continue to boost the population. The Walleye population will continue to be monitored annually to assess the health of the Walleye population.

MUSKIE

Muskie were first introduced into Fox Lake in 1999 and subsequently stocked in 2001 and have been stocked every other year from 2004 to 2018. The last two stockings were in October 2019 (N=475) and October 2022 (N=476). The recent 3 year gap in stocking was a byproduct of inconsistent statewide Muskie production, COVID related cessation of stocking in 2020, and a statewide reprioritization along with improvement in lessons learned with Muskie management. No Muskie were captured in gill nets or trap nets in the 2022 survey. Gill nets and trap nets are usually ineffective at sampling Muskie during our annual survey in September. Therefore, large frame trap nets are set every 5 years to sample the Muskie population. A survey utilizing the large frame trap nets was done in May 2022. No Muskies were sampled. Five years prior during the 2017 assessment Muskie were captured at a rate of 3.9 per net per day. During 2017, Muskie ranged in length from 10.8 to 50.1 inches and averaged 42.2 inches. The population estimate in 2016 (the last reliable estimate using 2017 as a recapture event) was 250 adults (193 to 307; 95 Percent Confidence Interval). Given the recent water quality issues, however, a special targeted LTN assessment was conducted during the spring of 2021. Five Muskie were caught in 3 days of netting with 2 nets each day (6 net nights). Muskies sampled ranged in length from 39.1 to 48.9 inches with an average length of 42.2 inches. Three males and 2 females were sampled. Therefore, it is strange that 0 Muskie were sampled in 2022. We suspect that the adult Muskie population has shifted to a much less abundant population, but Muskies are mostly likely still present. It is very likely that the originally stocked fish in 1999 and the following year class in 2001 are now gone from the lake due to old age. Since 2011 when PIT tagging was started on Fox Lake, 325 unique adult Muskie have been sampled and PIT tagged and 2,950 fingerling Muskie have been PIT tagged and stocked. A follow-up sampling event for Muskie will occur in the spring of 2023 to determine presence and size of individuals in the population.

CRAPPIE

Black Crappie were captured at a rate of 17.3 per trap net, which is within the normal range (1.8 to 21.2 per trap net) but down slightly from 23.0 per trap net in 2021. However, the catch rate is nearly equal to the long-term average of 17.0 per trap net since 1981. Fox Lake has had 8 successive years (2015-2022) of catch rates above or near the long-term average indicating a return of good numbers of crappie. Lengths of Black Crappie ranged from 4 to 13 inches in gill nets and trap nets and averaged nearly 7 inches in trap nets. The average and maximum lengths are similar to the past several years indicating potential slow growth. Black Crappie appear to be feeding successfully with most fish being plump. The Black Crappie population is self-sustaining and stable with at least 2 or 3 strong year classes present based on length frequency in trap nets. The management goal was exceeded because the catch rate was above the desired range.

The White Crappie catch rate in 2022 was 66.8 per trap net, which exceeded the upper expected range (0.5 to 6.6) and is the greatest on record since 1981. Additionally, the gill net catch rate was 20.3 per net, near the long term average of 20.1 per trap net. Several years of above average catch rates are good news and potentially a signal that good crappie fishing may be just around the corner. During the mid-to-late 2000's the Crappie population was dominated by many fish over 10 inches. This was largely due to hybridization that occurs when White and Black Crappie numbers are high. Currently, White Crappie lengths ranged from just under 5 inches to just over 10 inches and averaged 7 inches in the trap net sample. White Crappie, similarly to Black Crappie, did not appear to have a definitive increasing or decreasing body weight relationship as length increased. Unlike the past 7 years, White Crappie abundance exceeds Black Crappie abundance. When this occurs there is an increased probability of hybridization during spawning. Hybridization could lead to increased growth and maximum size attained by a future hybrid crappie population. Continued monitoring will evaluate growth and hybridization.

Multiple strong year classes are present and the fish, although somewhat slow growing, could attain 10 inches or greater. Annual surveys will monitor abundance and growth of Black and White Crappie.

OTHER SPECIES

The Yellow Perch catch rate in 2022 (0.2 per gill net) was lower than we would expect for lakes similar to Fox Lake. Catch rates of Yellow Perch have been characterized by extreme fluctuations from 2011 to 2016 followed by a drastic drop and maintenance of an extremely low abundance (less than 1 per gill net). This variability in gill net catches is most likely due to environmental conditions and potential resource scarcity and competition with increasing Black and White crappie populations. However, with only 7 Yellow Perch caught in gill nets and trap nets in 2022 additional stocking may be warranted. Yellow Perch were stocked by the Fox Lake Association during the spring of 2022, but those fish have not had time to spawn. While Yellow Perch abundance remains low, additional stocking will be implemented in 2023 to boost broodstock.

The Freshwater Drum catch rate was 111 per gill net, more than twice the long-term average (47.7 per gill net) and above the normal range of 4 to 32 per gill net for similar lakes. While the gill net catch rate was the greatest catch on record, the trap net catch rate was only 2.3 per net, less than the long-term average of 12 per net but above the normal range of 0.5 to 4.2 per trap net. There is some desire among the Fox Lake Association members and Fox Lake Conservation League to remove Freshwater Drum to reduce their relative abundance, however, past studies have shown that this may actually induce a reproduction response and can speed up growth in Freshwater Drum. Currently, the Freshwater Drum in the gill net and trap net sample range in length from 3 to 15 inches with an average length of 10.5 inches in the gill nets. With the exception of a few of the largest Freshwater Drum in the sample, all of these fish are potentially subject to predation by the existing Muskie population and the newly stocked adult Walleye. Predation coupled with potential commercial fish removal in the future may help to reduce Freshwater Drum abundance. However, this will not be a fast shift in abundance and could take several years with intensive stocking of gamefish to keep them in balance.

Additional species sampled included 198 Bigmouth Buffalo, 29 Bluegill, 2 Channel Catfish, 20 Common Carp, 6 Golden Shiner, 3 Quillback Carpsucker, and 1 Yellow Bullhead. Of these species, Bigmouth Buffalo are of particular concern. These fish, while native, can over populate and act as a source of competition for limited plankton resources due to their filter feeding which can shift the plankton community to one dominated by phytoplankton. They also have the ability to suspend sediments while looking for invertebrate food sources that can lead to internal nutrient loading and create poor water quality. The large 2013-2015 year classes of Bigmouth Buffalo appear to be a possible driver of poor water quality on Fox over the last few years. While those year classes of fish continue to grow and move through the fish community, their growth appears to be slower than other populations in the Windom area. Continued monitoring will be done to track changes in numbers and species caught in Fox Lake.

Fox Lake is managed for walleye primarily because of the species popularity and their willingness to eatfreshwater drum. In addition to providing a walleye fishery, the Windom Fisheries is evaluating the effectivenessof walleye for reducing/controlling the freshwater drum population. During the 1994 survey, over 70% of thewalleye had eaten young-of-the-year freshwater drum. Although there are a lot of walleye in Fox Lake and theydo eat freshwater drum, we do not have the information to say how long throughout the year walleye prey onfreshwater drum (because we only sampled the lake for one week). Only time will tell if walleye can be aneffective predator on freshwater drum. The walleye population was looking good in 1994. The net catches indicated that the population was 7 timeshigher than most lakes that are similar to Fox Lake. Walleye lengths ranged from 8.1 to 25.2 inches but themajority of the fish were 12 to 16 inches. We can't put the walleyes on the line for you but the fish werecertainly there. The northern pike population has always been pretty low when we have sampled Fox Lake. In 1994, the northernpike numbers were still low but there is a chance that you could catch a 12 to 20 pound fish. The commercialseiners caught about 115 northern pike during the winter and approximately 25 of these fish were from 12 to 24pounds. The fact that northern pike do not seem to be very successful in reproducing in Fox Lake may be anindication that there is insufficient quality spawning habitat. Only a few largemouth bass have ever been sampled in Fox Lake and unless the submerged vegetation increasesthe population will likely remain low. Bluegill is another species that really relies on submerged vegetationto have a good population. These species do best when there is enough vegetation to provide protection for theadults spawning and guarding their nests and then for the newly hatched fish as they grow during the summer. Asof 1994, the bluegill numbers had increased from previous surveys, but the population is still low. Black crappie have been low during the last few years but they were successful in producing a good year classin 1994. If this year class survives beyond their first year of life it should help to improve the black crappiepopulation. Black crappie lengths ranged from 3.7 to 12.0 but most of the fish were about 4 inches.

Fox Lake is a 1,041 acre lake located near Sherburn in Martin County. Fox Lake is in lake class 24, is about 3.5 miles long and has 9.6 miles of shoreline. The lakes bottom consists of sand, gravel, rubble, and muck. Fox lake is managed primarily for walleye with largemouth bass, black crappie, bluegill, and northern pike managed as secondary species. In the past, Fox Lake was stocked with northern pike to control freshwater drum. Recent surveys have indicated walleye may be more effective than pike. Presently the lake is stocked with walleye fingerlings two of three years at a rate of 1.5 pounds of fingerlings per littoral acre to control the freshwater drum population.The walleye population would be considered normal to high for lakes similar to Fox Lake. Lengths of walleye ranged from 7.5 to almost 26 inches and averaged 16.5 inches. The average weight of walleye in Fox was 2 pounds. Our data collected during the 1996 population assessment suggest that the population is well balanced. Fish from 1994 and 1996 were the result of natural reproduction.The northern pike population would be considered normal for lakes similar to Fox Lake. Northern pike catch rates have increased from 0.1 fish/net in 1994 to 0.5 fish/net in 1996. Lengths of northern pike ranged from 25 to 39 inches and averaged 32.6 inches. The average weight of northern pike collected during the survey was over 9 pounds. In the past, northern pike were stocked to control freshwater drum. Our data suggests they have been ineffective and walleye may have better success controlling drum.The yellow perch population has been relatively stable since 1994. Numbers of yellow perch would be considered normal compared to lakes similar to Fox Lake. Lengths of yellow perch ranged from 4 to almost 11 inches and averaged 9 inches. The average weight of yellow perch in Fox Lake was almost ? pound.The bluegill population would be considered low to average for lakes similar to Fox Lake. Lengths of bluegill collected during the 1996 population assessment 3.5 to 8.5 inches and averaged almost 6 inches. The average weight of bluegill was about 1/4 lb.The black crappie population would be considered average for lakes similar to Fox Lake. Catch rates for black crappie have decreased from 1995 but are still considered normal. Lengths of black crappie collected during the 1996 population assessment ranged from 3.5 to 10.5 inches and averaged about 7.5 inches. The average weight of black crappie was 1/3 lb.The largemouth bass population was up from previous years. This was attributed to a good hatch of largemouth bass in 1996. The largemouth bass collected during the 1996 survey were from natural reproduction. The black bullhead population is good compared to lakes similar to Fox Lake. Lengths of black bullhead ranged from 5 to 13 inches and averaged 10.6 inches. The average weight of black bullhead was almost 3/4 lb. Black bullhead should provide excellent fishing opportunities in the future.To promote and maintain a healthy fish population, pollution and other inputs need to be controlled. Fish habitat is directly affected by water quality. Nutrient, sediment and other waste inputs can drastically alter the chemical and physical components of a Lake. It is paramount to maintain if not improve the current water quality of Fox Lake through watershed management to preserve this fishery for future generations to enjoy.

The Yellow Perch catch rate in 2023 was 0 per gill net, which has happened 3 times since 2018 and indicates a very low abundance of Yellow Perch in the lake. Yellow Perch were stocked during the spring of 2022, but a resulting year class has not been observed yet. While Yellow Perch abundance remains low stocking will be done in 2024 with adults if a source is found.

The Freshwater Drum catch rate was 118.3 per gill net, more than twice the long-term average (49.6 per gill net) and above the interquartile range of 4.0 to 32.3 per gill net for class 24 lakes. While the gill net catch rate was the greatest catch on record, the trap net catch rate was only 9.6 per net, less than the long-term average of 12.0 per net. There is some desire among the Fox Lake Association members and Fox Lake Conservation League to remove Freshwater Drum to reduce their relative abundance, however, past studies have shown that this may actually induce a reproduction response and can speed up growth in Freshwater Drum. Currently, the Freshwater Drum in the gill net and trap net sample range in length from 5 to 13.5 inches with an average length of just under 10 inches in the gill nets. With the exception of a few of the largest Freshwater Drum in the sample, all of these fish are potentially subject to predation by the existing Muskie population. Predation coupled with potential commercial fish removal in the future may help to reduce Freshwater Drum abundance. However, this will not be a fast shift in abundance and could take several years with intensive stocking of gamefish to keep them in balance. A potential consideration is to stock yearling or adult Muskie instead of fingerling Muskie, which will serve 2 purposes. First, larger Muskie will act as a predator right away and larger Muskie have a greater chance of survival to larger sizes and thus eat more fish over time.

Additional species sampled included Bigmouth Buffalo (N=258), Bluegill (N=8), Channel Catfish (N=7), Common Carp (N=41), Golden Shiner (N=1), Largemouth Bass (N=1), Quillback Carpsucker (N=2), and Yellow Bullhead (N=2). Of these species, Bigmouth Buffalo are of particular concern. These fish, while native, can over populate and act as a source of competition for limited plankton resources due to their filter feeding which can shift the plankton community to one dominated by phytoplankton. They also have the ability to suspend sediments while looking for invertebrate food sources that can lead to internal nutrient loading and create poor water quality. The large 2013-2015 year classes of Bigmouth Buffalo appear to be a possible driver of poor water quality on Fox over the last few years. While those year classes of fish continue to grow and move through the fish community, their growth appears to be slower than other populations in the Windom area. Continued monitoring will be done to track changes in numbers and species caught in Fox Lake.

Fox Lake is a 1041 acre lake that is managed primarily for walleye. Additionally, Fox Lake is managed secondarily for black crappie, bluegill, channel catfish, muskellunge, and white crappie. Lakeshore development has increased in the last 9 years. Dissolved oxygen in the winter has never been a problem due in part to the open water from heated discharge from the power plant and due to the deeper water in the east end of the lake. A recreational survey to assess angling effort and catch is scheduled for the summer of 2001 and winter of 2001-2002. Walleye stocking regime calls for fry stocking three out of four years (1998, 1999, and 2000). Muskellunge fingerlings (yearlings) are scheduled to be stocked in the fall of 2001 and 2003. The average walleye gill net catch rate was 6.83 fish/net. The catch rate was higher than the upper average range (6.33 fish/net) for this lake class. Walleyes captured in gill nets range in size from 9.06 inches to 25.28 inches with a mean of 17.07 inches. The walleye size structure was definitely worth your limited angler hours. Artificial or natural recruitment of walleye is an issue the DNR monitors closely which is why the fall electrofishing for Age 0 walleye in 2000 was done. Fall electrofishing found 14 Age 0 walleye/hr which indicated moderate survival of fry or natural reproduction. Either scenario indicates some recruitment of walleye into the population. Fox Lake has some real potential for walleye action.The average black crappie trap net catch rate was 18.75 fish/net. While catch rates for bluegill have been historically better, the sizes of fish in the system are nice. The average channel catfish gill net catch rate was 6.67 fish/net. The catch rate for channel catfish have been fairly consistent in the last 4 years. Age 3 (321 mm) and Age 5 ( =423 mm) channel catfish tend to be slow growing so reasonable harvest should be self-imposed. Fishing for channel catfish can be excellent and relaxing during those "dog days" of summer.No muskellunge were captured in trap nets but 4 were captured in gill nets during the survey in 2000. Fox Lake, near the town of Sherburn, is a 1,041 acre lake in Martin County. Fox Lake is a unique lake for the Windom Area as the opportunity exists to catch muskellunge. Fox Lake is managed primarily for walleye and muskellunge and secondarily for black and white crappie and channel catfish. A re-survey was conducted the week of September 11, 2006 using gill nets, trap nets, and seine hauls. The reason we use all these different gears is because each gear is used to index certain species in the population. In 2006, submergent aquatic vegetation was comparatively more dense than historical vegetation surveys. This will likely be good for natural reproduction for many of our gamefish in Fox Lake.

The catch rate of walleye in gill nets was 2.8/gill net, which was within the expected range for this type of lake. The average length captured was 15.4 inches, but ranged from 8.8 to 26.8 inches. Although the catch rate for walleyes has been historically higher at times, the variety of sizes may indicate a more stable population. Walleye grew from 1.5 to 2.3 inches per year. In 21 assessments on Fox Lake since 1981, the walleye catch rate has exceeded the upper normal range (6.3 walleye/gn) only 8 times. The current stocking plan calls for stocking walleye fingerlings at 1 pound per littoral acre or around 780 pounds per year. A variety of walleye sizes can be caught if the effort is put forth.

Muskellunge data and status will be further determined in a spring 2007 assessment. Although we sample muskellunge in our gears during our annual surveys on Fox Lake, the number of fish captured is limited and therefore their status is difficult to speculate on. Only 1 muskellunge was captured in a gill net during the 2006 survey. The captured fish was 24.7 inches and two years old.

Channel catfish have done well in Fox Lake since 1997. The catch rate of channel catfish in gill nets in 2006 was 6.7 fish/gill net. Channel catfish have not been stocked in Fox Lake since 1986, which means the population has been self-sustaining. Most of the fish captured ranged from 17.2 to 26.1 inches with an average of 19.4 inches. Windom Area staff have observed an indirect correlation between black bullhead abundance and channel catfish abundance. Typically, Windom Area lakes have relatively high bullhead abundance except in lakes where channel catfish are abundant. Most of the fish were naturally reproduced in 2000. If you are looking for something to fish for during those hot summer months, Fox Lake channel catfish will likely provide some good angling.

Both black and white crappie have thrived in Fox Lake and have consistently been abundant since 1997. In 2006, both species grew around an inch per year and averaged around 8 inches long. While the proportion of black to white crappie has varied over the years, the white crappie population has been more abundant. Good numbers and sizes of both black and white crappies can be caught, especially in the spring.

While bluegill numbers appear to be similar to years past, natural reproduction of bluegills in 2006 was excellent. Seine hauls sampled about 1600 young of the year bluegill. Natural reproduction of bluegill and largemouth bass are often related to the amount of aquatic vegetation. The 2006 aquatic vegetation (sago pondweed) was quite abundant on the south and east sides of the lake from shore out to around 5 feet deep. Most of the adult bluegills were 5.5 to 7.5 inches. It is quite possible that the abundance of bluegills could be higher in years to come.

Other species captured in 2006 were common carp, yellow bullhead, green sunfish, hybrid sunfish, and shiners.

Efforts to improve the health of the lake should focus on best management practices within the watershed. Improvements and education in land stewardship will often have secondary benefits to the lake in the way of quality and quantity of habitat. Generally, improvements in the quality and quantity of lake habitat will mean direct improvements of the fishery.

Fox Lake, near the town of Sherburn, is a 1,041-acre lake in Martin County with a maximum depth of 20 feet. In the last few years aquatic vegetation (mostly sago pondweed) has gradually increased in abundance. Generally when we see increasing aquatic vegetation in an area lake, it is a result of increasing water clarity. Sago pondweed is important for fish and wildlife as it provides nursery and feeding habitat for small fish as well as cover from predators. It is possible that seasonal (spring/early summer) changes in water clarity have increased, which may have brought on this resurgence of sago pondweed. Sago is valuable from the water quality standpoint as nutrients are tied up in the aquatic vegetation instead of being available for algae production. Fox Lake is managed primarily for walleye and muskellunge and secondarily for channel catfish, white crappie, and black crappie. A population assessment was conducted during the week of September 9, 2007 using 6 gill nets and 12 trap nets.

Walleye abundance has increased slightly the last couple of years, but historical catch rates have been better. The average length walleye sampled in gill nets in 2007 was 14.6 inches, but ranged from 8.3 to 26.3 inches. Six year classes of walleye were sampled with most (91%) of the fish being Age 1 (8.1 inches), Age 2 (10.0 inches), and Age 3 (11.9 inches). The walleyes sampled are likely from fingerling stocking, but natural reproduction has occurred in the past on Fox Lake. Based on the netting results, there are a few larger walleye to target despite their apparent lower numbers.

One of the problems with assessing muskellunge populations is the difficulty in sampling them. Annual surveys done in September have sampled very few muskellunge since they were introduced into Fox Lake. Only 1 muskellunge was captured in gill nets during the annual population assessment in 2007. The fish was nearly 15 inches and likely from the fall 2006 stocking. We did some additional netting (35-trap net sets) during the spring of 2007 to supplement our annual assessments. Unfortunately, our nets only sampled 3 muskellunge, which averaged 37.5 inches in length. On May 10, 2007, the commercial operator captured 6 muskellunge during a seine haul. Total lengths ranged from 28.7 to 45.8 inches with a mean of 40.1 inches. It would appear from this information that there are legal fish to be caught.

The freshwater drum catch rate in gill nets was the lowest since 2002 while the size structure was the largest in 4 years. This suggests that the predators (muskellunge, walleye, and channel catfish) are eating smaller drum.

Channel catfish numbers remain high in Fox Lake. Average total length was 18 inches, but ranged from 17.8 to 28.7 inches. Catch rate since 2002 has averaged nearly 11 channel catfish/set, which was equal to the catch rate in 2007. No channel catfish were captured less than 17 inches long, which may eventually benefit walleye numbers. Channel catfish have not been stocked since 1986, which suggests the population is self-sustaining after this many years. Those hot summer days could provide the angler some great catfishing with the potential of a trophy.

The catch rate of black crappie in gill nets was the highest ever recorded. Typically, trap nets have been a better indicator of crappie abundance. The average length black crappie sampled in trap nets was 8.6 inches, but they ranged from 5.6 to 10.8 inches. Typically, black crappies tend to do better than white crappie in lakes with higher clarity water. Based on the ratio of black to white crappies in trap nets, the odds of catching white crappie are better.

The white crappie catch rate in trap nets was 28.9/set, which was more than 4 times the expected range. Sizes of white and black crappie were nearly identical. Total lengths averaged 8.5 inches, but ranged from 7.3 to 10.1 inches. Most (84%) of the fish were 8-9.5 inches.

Yellow perch catch rate in gill nets was 20.5/set, which was within the expected range (2.0 to 27.9/set). Since 2001, the abundance of yellow perch seems to be increasing steadily. In fact, the catch rate in 2007 has increased nearly 10 times that of the 2001 catch rate. Average length was 7.3 inches, but the range was from 6.1 to 9.4 inches. The chance of catching perch has been increasing since 2001 and sizes will be respectable in a year or so.

Historically, bluegill catch rates have been within the expected range only 3 times since 1981. The bluegill catch rate in trap nets in 2007 was 2.7/set, which was equal to the catch rate in 2005. Total lengths in 2007 averaged just over 7 inches. Last years six seine hauls captured nearly 1600 Age 0 bluegill. It is possible that these fish were not large enough to be captured by trap nets in 2007. With the high catch rate of Age 0 bluegill in the seine hauls last year and the resurgence of sago pondweed in 2007, catch rates of bluegills may increase in successive annual surveys.

Black bullhead abundance continues to be low compared to other Windom Area lakes. The catch rate in gill nets was 1.5/set and 1.2/set in trap nets. Long-term abundance of black bullhead has been declining since 1985.

Other species captured were bigmouth buffalo, common carp, green sunfish, largemouth bass, and yellow bullhead.

INTRODUCTION

Fox Lake is a 1,041 acre lake located in south-central Minnesota near the city of Sherburn in Martin County. Fox Lake has a maximum depth of 20 feet with nearly 75 percent of the lake having water less than 15 feet deep. Minnesota lakes managed for fishing are grouped into classes based on physical and chemical similarities and Fox Lake is assigned to lake class 24. Lake class 24 consists of shallow relatively turbid lakes high in nutrients with a smaller littoral area and irregular shape. The lake-to-watershed ratio for Fox Lake is 4-to-1, which indicates a relatively small influence of the watershed to the lake. Watershed improvements have helped the return of aquatic vegetation. As a result water clarity is gradually increasing. A Martin County Soil and Watershed District led program started in 2012 is focused on further improving watershed conditions for Fox Lake as well other Martin County Lakes. Improvements in the watershed for Fox Lake will continue to show up as improvements in water quality and clarity within the lake that will ultimately lead to healthier conditions for the fish community.

Like many lakes in southern Minnesota, Fox Lake is managed primarily for Walleye and secondarily for panfish; in this case crappie. However, Fox Lake is unique because it is also managed primarily for Muskellunge and is the southernmost Muskellunge lake in the state, which provides a unique angling opportunity. In addition, Fox Lake has been gill netted and trap netted annually since 1991, which has provided an exceptional fish catch history to analyze fish population trends and make the best fish management decisions. Finally, unlike many lakes in southern Minnesota, Fox Lake has never been aerated during the winter and provides a more stable dissolved oxygen profile during winter when compared to other area lakes. Ultimately, Fox Lake has proven to be a valuable and unique resource in southern Minnesota for lakeshore owners, local and regional anglers, as well as general recreational users.

The management goals for Fox Lake are to maintain a Walleye population at an abundance that will consistently yield gill net catches above 6 fish per net with a balanced length distribution (fish of all possible sizes in the sample). Another management goal is to continue efforts to establish a fishery for trophy size Muskellunge. Lastly, another goal is to maintain secondary populations of crappie within interquartile ranges for trap net catches which are 0.5 to 6.6 fish per net for white crappie and 1.8 to 21.2 fish per net for Black Crappie. Populations of the above mentioned species will be maintained through stocking (Walleye and Muskellunge) or natural reproduction (White and Black Crappie). In order to assess the management goals for Fox Lake, a fish population assessment is conducted each September. The following information outlines the information collected during the latest population assessment in September 2014 using 12 trap nets and 6 gill nets.

WALLEYE

The expected gill net catch rate of Walleye in Fox Lake is between 1.2 and 6.3 per net and the expected range for the trap net catch rate is between 0.3 and 1.2 per net. The gill net catch rate in 2014 was 5.7 per net which is within the expected range and nearly equal to the management goal of 6 per net. In addition, the trap net catch rate was 1.3 per net which is equal to a normal catch rate for lakes similar to Fox Lake. Historically, the Fox Lake gill net catch rate has been sporadic with catches ranging from 0.5 to 45.2 from 1981 to 2001 with an average catch rate of 9.8 per gill net during that same time frame. Since 2002, the catch rates have varied to a lesser degree from 0.5 to 5.7 with an average catch rate of 2.4 Walleye per gill net indicating a more stable and less abundant fish population. The reduction in the average catch rate from 9.8 Walleye per gill net from 1981 to 2001 to 2.4 Walleye per gill net from 2002 to 2013 is not easily explainable and is most likely the result of many factors. From 1979 to 2009 Fox Lake was stocked with Walleye fry, fingerlings, yearlings, and adults. Analyzing the catch rate after each stocking, it appeared that the highest catch rates were correlated to fry stockings in 1983 and 1984 and intensive fingerling stocking in 1992 and 1993. But, suppressed catch rates from 2002 to 2013 occur during similar stocking strategies indicating other factors may be involved. Since 1998, competition for limited prey resources has never been higher in Fox Lake with the emergence of robust populations of White crappie, Black Crappie, Largemouth Bass, and Channel Catfish and the decline of Black Bullhead as an additional forage base. In addition, Muskellunge have been stocked in Fox Lake since 1999 adding an additional predator. Starting in 2010, Walleye frylings (2 to 3 inch fish) have been stocked annually showing some improvement in gill net catch rates, 3.2 to 3.5 fish per gill net from 2011 to 2012. However, competition with other predators or other unknown factors appears to continue to suppress the Walleye population abundance. In response, fingerling Walleye were stocked in the fall of 2013. The gill net catch rate in 2014 (5.7 per net) was 1.6 to 3.1 times greater than catch rates over the previous 3 years. All age-1 Walleye (2013 year class) caught in the 2014 gill net sample were inspected for oxytetracycline (OTC) marks on their inner ear bones (known as otoliths). An OTC mark would indicate that the Walleye is from the fryling stocking (marked fish) in 2013 and not the fingerling stocked fish in 2013. Four of the 23 age-1 Walleye (17%) had an OTC mark. This indicated that the fryling stocking may have only contributed 17% of the Walleye in the 2013 year class. Therefore, the fingerling stocking was highly successful making up 83% of the age-1 fish, assuming no natural reproduction occurred. The size structure of the population was also good in 2014 and shows promise for the perpetuation of catchable size Walleye in the future. Walleye of all sizes are becoming more common in anglers catches with local fishing reports indicating the "best Walleye fishing in recent years". The Walleye in the sample in 2014 ranged from 10.0 to 25.0 inches with an average size of 13.9 inches in the gill net sample and 19.6 in the trap net sample. Aging of otoliths from gill net fish revealed 5 age groups (ages 1, 4, 5, 6, and 17). Interestingly, only 2 age-4 fish and 4 age-1 fish can be directly linked to fryling stocking showing a limited contribution of fryling stocking from the Walleye in the aged sample (n=34). Regardless of stocking method, Walleye in the sample were healthy and had good body condition. Future abundance of the Walleye population appears directly related to other species leading to competition for limited food sources at times and potential negative interactions at the time Walleye are stocked. Improvement of the Walleye population abundance will most likely occur if White Crappie, Black Crappie, or Channel Catfish abundance decreases (none are stocked). Additionally, it may be beneficial to stock Walleye fry in the spring of each year and add additional fingerling Walleye if needed. Without a reduced abundance of other predators in Fox Lake or a change in management it is likely that the population will not exceed current abundance levels.

MUSKELLUNGE

Muskie have been stocked into Fox Lake starting in 1999 with subsequent stockings in 2001, 2004, 2006, 2008, 2010, 2012, and 2014. No natural reproduction of Muskie has been documented in Fox Lake so all fish present are from stocking. Ages of Muskie in Fox Lake range from 2 to 17 years old. Muskies over 10 years old have the ability to reach trophy size so potential exists for the Fox Lake Muskie population to have trophy individuals present in the lake. In 2014, 2 Muskies were caught in the trap net sample (0.2 fish per net). Muskie are not effectively sampled with gill nets or standard trap nets and the long-term catch rates from 2000 to 2014 reflect that with gill net catch rates varying from only 0 to 0.7 fish per net. Therefore, in 2011 a long-term Muskie study was started focusing on obtaining information leading to a population estimate that will help determine the ideal stocking rate for Fox Lake. Large-frame trap nets were used in 2011, 2012, and 2013 in the spring to capture Muskie, particularly Muskie greater than 34 inches (considered mature adults). In 2011, 140 Muskie were caught over 2 weeks in May. The Muskie ranged in length from 14.5 to 48.9 inches with an average length of 41.7 inches. In 2012, 45 Muskie were caught over 3 weeks in April and May. Muskie ranged in length from 31.0 to 48.7 inches with an average length of 41.5 inches. In 2013, 107 Muskie were sampled over 2 weeks in April and May. Muskie ranged in length from 29.0 to 50.4 inches with an average length of 41.1 inches. Fluctuations in catch rates from year-to-year is the result of vastly different spring water temperatures and duration of spring spawning conditions. Population estimates from the 3 year study put the population number of Muskie greater than 34 inches somewhere between 190 to 287 individuals with 95% confidence. This indicates the population is doing well and many large Muskies are present in the lake. The Muskie population will be monitored bi-annually with large frame trap nets starting in the spring 2015.

CRAPPIE

Two species of crappie (Black and White) have been sampled historically in Fox Lake. However, in 2014 only Black Crappie were sampled in gill nets and trap nets. The catch rates of Black Crappie were 6.8 fish per gill net (n=41) and 6.9 fish per trap net (n=83). Catch rates of Black Crappie are not necessarily the best indicator of how well the population is doing. Black Crappie catch rates tend to vary widely from year to year and even from season to season and the population size structure is more indicative of the overall health of the population in the lake. Black Crappie ranged in size from 3.4 to 13.6 inches with an average length of 6.3 inches in the gill net sample and 6.1 inches in the trap net sample. Overall, it appears that the Black Crappie population has a balanced size structure. Production of younger Black Crappie (3-4 inch fish) in the population in 2014 also helped to balance the Black Crappie population. Future assessments, including potential spring trap netting, will monitor the Black Crappie populations to determine relative abundance, size structure, and recruitment.

YELLOW PERCH

Yellow Perch in Fox Lake are the main forage for the Walleye and muskellunge populations. Fluctuations in the abundance of the Yellow Perch population can lead to fluctuations in the Walleye and Muskellunge populations. The historical catch rates of Yellow Perch in the gill nets range from a low of 0.3 per gill net in 1992 to a high of 80.5 in 2012 and from 0 per trap net in 1986, 1989, and 1992 to 22.6 per trap net in 1997. The 2014 gill net catch rate was a more typical catch rate of 25.0 fish per gill net (n=150). However, over the past 4 years the Yellow Perch population has fluctuated from lows of 1.5 (2013) and 1.8 per gill net (2011) to a high of 80.5 per gill net (2012). A cause in the swing in catch rate from very low to very high is not completely understood, but growth of vast aquatic vegetation beds over the last 5 years may give the Yellow Perch population a place to successfully hide from survey nets as well as from predators. Increased survival of the Yellow Perch in Fox Lake will improve the chances of sustaining a consistent abundance of forage sized fish in the lake that will help the Yellow Perch population sustain itself. The size of Yellow Perch in the 2014 sample ranged from 5.2 to 8.8 inches with an average length of 7.8 inches in the gill net sample and 8.0 inches in the trap net sample. This range of sizes may be a little large for Walleye forage but it is adequate for Muskellunge, and at levels that will allow for plentiful availability.

OTHER SPECIES

Other species of fish caught in the 2014 survey were Bigmouth Buffalo (278), Black Bullhead (84), Channel Catfish (20), Common Carp (26), Freshwater Drum (532), and Largemouth Bass (1). Of the species listed above, Bigmouth Buffalo, Channel Catfish, and Freshwater Drum are the most prevalent. Bigmouth Buffalo in the population are mainly 4 to 7 inches indicating successful spawn in recent years. Channel Catfish are doing well in Fox Lake and currently range in length from 20.4 to 28.9 inches with an average weight of 5.7 pounds. The abundant Channel Catfish population is the suspected reason why the bullhead population is not as prevalent as it has been in the past due to predation and competition for common resources. Finally, Freshwater Drum are the most abundant "rough" fish in the population with a gill net catch rate of 42.5 fish per net. Freshwater Drum in the 2014 sample ranged in length from 4.8 to 19.4 inches with an average of 10.9 inches in the gill net sample and 14.9 inches in the trap net sample. With an abundant Muskie and potentially expanding Walleye population, Freshwater Drum will increasingly become important as forage for larger Muskellunge and Walleye.

SUMMARY

Overall, the Fox Lake fish community appears to be doing well with a diverse fish community that is seeing improvements in managed fish species abundance and/or size structure. Further Improvements in the lake for the fish community should focus on best management practices in the watershed. Improvements and education in land stewardship will often have secondary benefits to the lake in the way of quality and quantity of habitat. Generally, improvements in the quality and quantity of lake habitat will result in direct improvements for the fish community. Wise use of our natural resources makes us good stewards to the land and water that all of us use every day.
