A Muskie survey using large trap nets to determine the number of Muskie was done during the spring of 2017. 125 Muskie were sampled on Fox Lake in the spring of 2017. Nets were large frame trap nets that were set on April 24th and checked and reset in the same location each day until April 28th for a total of 4 days of sets. Of the 125 Muskies captured, 12 were recaptured more than once and 2 were less than 30 inches resulting in 111 unique Muskie over 30 inches (referred to as adults) caught in 2017. Twenty of the 111 were newly encountered in the 2017 netting. Each Muskie was tagged with a PIT tag if not tagged in a previous year. Muskies were tagged with PIT tags in 2011, 2012, 2013, 2015, and 2016 for a previous population estimate study so some captured muskies already had a tag.

Of the 111 unique Muskie over 30 inches there were 65 males and 42 females and 4 undetermined. The average length of males and females was 40.3 inches and 45.7 inches respectively with an overall average of 42.3 inches. The minimum length of males and females was 34.9 inches and 38.1 inches respectively. The maximum length of males and females was 45.5 inches and 50.1 inches respectively. In addition to an excellent size distribution, the population abundance was also good. Population estimates (# over 30 inches) have been done since 2011 on Fox Lake, with the exception of 2014. The most recent population estimate was for 2016 as the 2017 netting finalized the 2016 estimate. The 2011 estimate was 258, the 2012 estimate was 210, the 2013 estimate was 193, the 2015 population estimate was 242, and the 2016 population estimate was 248. Since 2011, the population estimate has remained relatively stable from a low of 193 to a high of 258. Additionally, due to increase sampling and confidence the 2016 of 248 is the most reliable. This amounts to 1 Muskie over 30 inches for every 4 acres of water on Fox Lake. This is excellent for Fox Lake, which at times can have high densities of Freshwater Drum, Bigmouth Buffalo, and Common Carp. Those fish, especially Bigmouth Buffalo, provide excellent forage and energy to grow the Fox Lake Muskies to trophy sizes.

The Muskellunge population appears to be doing well in Fox Lake with fish over 50 inches in the sample. Angling for Muskie can range from excellent to difficult on Fox Lake. Water clarity reductions due to temporary algae blooms can hamper techniques that traditional Muskie anglers are used to. Don't be afraid to vary the style of angling on Fox Lake. Be willing to utilize lures that mimic prey that are more common to southern Minnesota. For example, due to a recent boom of young Bigmouth Buffalo, anglers would be smart to utilize lures that mimic those soft bodied rough fish. Good luck landing the big one!

Additional spring netting will be conducted in the future to further monitor Muskellunge in Fox Lake. If anyone is interested in helping sample Muskellunge as part of the spring assessment they are welcome to contact the Windom DNR office at 507-831-2900 to volunteer.

As part of a standard survey on Fox Lake during 2017, an additional nearshore survey was conducted from 4 August 2017 to 7 August 2017. Sampling for the nearshore survey involved backpack electrofishing and seining in wadable water at locations along the lakeshore. Fox Lake had 12 shoreline locations, 100 feet in length, where both backpack electrofishing and seining with one-eighth inch mesh was conducted. Seventeen species of fish were sampled. Species included Bigmouth Buffalo, Black Crappie, Bluegill, Channel Catfish, Freshwater Drum, Golden Shiner, Green Sunfish, Hybrid Sunfish, Johnny Darter, Largemouth Bass, Muskellunge, Spotfin Shiner, Spottail Shiner, Walleye, White Crappie, Yellow Bullhead, and Yellow Perch. Of those species caught, 7 had young-of-the-year representation indicating successful reproduction. Young-of-the-year species were Bigmouth Buffalo, Black Crappie, Bluegill, Freshwater Drum, Largemouth Bass, White Crappie, and Yellow Perch. Sunfishes (including Bluegill, Crappies, and Bass) and minnows (including Buffalo and Shiners) made up the majority of the fish which is indicative of good vegetative cover and critical habitat for those species. A previous IBI survey was conducted in 2010 and sampled some species not found in 2017. Species not found in 2017 were Black Bullhead, Common Carp, and Emerald Shiner. During the standard survey in 2017, Black Bullhead and Common Carp were present, so the only species absent was Emerald Shiner. It is quite possible that Emerald Shiner could actually have been either misidentified young Spotfin Shiner or young Spottail Shiner. Therefore, species present within Fox Lake has remained stable for the past 8 or more years. Fox Lake appears to be a relatively healthy southern Minnesota Lake based solely on the fish community data.

An assessment of lakeshore habitat on Fox Lake was conducted on 7/6/2017. The assessment consisted of 91 survey sites evenly spaced 200 meters around the lake. The average lake wide habitat score was 67.0(+/- 2.3), indicating overall lakeshore habitat quality was moderate (66-84). Sites with moderate habitat quality have a high percentage of unaltered habitat but at least one zone has lower habitat quality than a high scoring site. Undeveloped sites may score moderate if they naturally lack a habitat component. Developed sites that retain a high percentage of natural habitat areas may score in this range. Approximately 69 percent of the sites were developed with a mean score of 55.7(+/- 2.1), while undeveloped sites had a mean score of 92.5(+/- 1.3). This habitat survey was designed to provide a means to quantify and compare lakeshore habitat between lakes. The Fox Lake shoreline habitat score is lower than the statewide lake score average of 73.6.

Fox Lake is a 1,041-acre lake located near the city of Sherburn in Martin County. Fox Lake has a maximum depth of 20 feet and is not aerated. Fox Lake's watershed is relatively small compared to the size of the lake (4 acres of land for every 1 acre of water). Watershed improvements and the closing of a diversion structure on the west end has helped water quality and has allowed aquatic vegetation to return, which provides habitat for several species of fish. In addition, curly-leaf pondweed can become abundant in the southeast area of Fox Lake when conditions are favorable. Fox Lake provides a unique fishery, in that it is managed primarily for Muskellunge and Walleye and secondarily for crappie, making it one of only two lake systems in the Windom fisheries management area that provide Muskellunge angling opportunities. An annual fish community survey is conducted on Fox Lake and was done during the first week of September 2018 using six gill nets and 12 trap nets.

WALLEYE
In 2018, the Walleye catch rate was 0.5 per gill net, which is below the expected range of 1.2 to 6.3 per gill net and is tied for the lowest catch rate observed since sampling began. Prior to 2018, the Walleye catch rate was experiencing a resurgence with a three year increasing trend. The lack of Walleye captured in gill nets is a bit concerning, however, a catch rate of 1 per trap net in 2018 falls within the normal range for similar lakes. During the week of sampling in 2018 Walleye may have remained near shore away from the gill nets. Gill nets are an offshore sampling method and capture fish in deeper water. One year with a poor catch rate followed by 3 high years does not indicate a population level failure, but instead indicates behavior or catchability changes during the week of sampling. Fox Lake is sampled every year and 2019 sampling should help to give a better indication of the Walleye population in Fox Lake. If the catch rate remains low, then there may be a need to alter Walleye management. Three ages of Walleye were sampled including Walleye from 2014, 2015, and 2016, which all correspond to stocking. Lengths of Walleye ranged from nearly 11 to just over 22 inches and averaged 13 inches in gill nets and 14 inches in trap nets. Growth of Walleye in Fox Lake was slower, but not surprising given the type of lake, for southern Minnesota with Walleye only reaching 11.5 inches by age 3. Walleyes in the sample were in fair health, not skinny but not fat. Future stocking may include the newly reestablished Lower Mississippi Strain Walleye from the Lake Sarah egg take which may help to boost the population in Fox Lake. Walleye angling has been better on Fox Lake over the past 4 years and should continue to be good in 2019.

MUSKELLUNGE
Muskellunge were introduced in Fox Lake in 1999, were stocked in 2001 and have been stocked every other year since 2004. No Muskellunge were captured in the annual standard survey because standard gill nets and trap nets do not effectively sample them. In the 2017 assessment using large frame trap nets, Muskellunge were captured at a rate of 3.9 per set per day. Muskellunge ranged in length from 11 to just over 50 inches and averaged 42 inches. The population estimate in 2016 (the last reliable estimate) was 241 adults or equivalent to 1 adult muskellunge every 4 acres. Since 2011, 325 unique adult Muskellunge have been sampled and PIT tagged and 1,999 fingerling Muskie have been PIT tagged and stocked. Trophy Muskie are now present in Fox Lake and catch rates have been above statewide averages so targeting them should be easier than usual for Muskie fishing. Get out there and give it a try, you just might find you are the one that gets hooked!

CRAPPIE
In 2018, Black Crappie were captured at a rate of 35.2 per trap net, which is greater than the expected catch rate range of 1.8 to 21.2 per trap net. Historically, the catch rate is greater than the long term average of nearly 14.6 per trap net and is the third highest ever recorded. Fox Lake has had 4 successive years of catch rates above the long-term average indicating a potential return of good numbers of crappie. Lengths of Black Crappie ranged from 3 to 14 inches in gill nets and trap nets and averaged 7.5 inches in trap nets. The average length is an increase of a half inch since 2017 indicating decent growth. Black Crappie are healthy and appear to be finding adequate food. The Black Crappie population is self-sustaining and stable with at least 2 strong age groups present based on lengths observed in trap nets. Black Crappie fishing is Fox Lake's bread and butter and it should continue to get better in the years to come with some big fish present.

The White Crappie catch rate in 2018 was 1.5 per trap net, which is within the expected catch range of 0.5 to 6.6 on similar lakes. White Crappie ranged in length from just under 6 inches to nearly 10 inches and averaged 7 inches in the trap net sample. Although the two species of crappie can coexist, Black Crappie are dominating the Fox Lake crappie fishery.

OTHER SPECIES
The Yellow Perch catch rate in 2018 was 0.5 per gill net, less than the expected catch rates for similar lakes (2.0 to 27.9 per gill net). The catch rate of Yellow Perch has been up and down since 2011. This variability in gill net success is most likely due to environmental conditions and not true population changes. Lengths of Yellow Perch ranged from 7 to almost 8 inches and averaged just over 7 inches. The Freshwater Drum catch rate was slightly above 71 per gill net, above the long term average of 45 per gill net and higher than the expected catch rate for similar lakes (4.0 to 32.3 per gill net). There is a desire by local anglers to remove Freshwater Drum to reduce numbers, however, past studies have shown that this only creates a reproduction response and actually speeds up growth and reproduction in Freshwater Drum. Freshwater Drum cannot be removed fast enough by humans to truly make an impact. Control of Freshwater Drum should instead focus on competition (Bluegill or Crappie) and predation (large Muskie). The Channel Catfish catch rate was 0.33 per gill net. Only 2 Channel Catfish were caught that were 13 inches and 23 inches. Fourteen Bluegill, 5 to just under 8 inches in length, were sampled in trap nets. Other species sampled included Bigmouth Buffalo, Common Carp, and Quillback Carpsucker.

Thirty seven muskie were sampled in 87 large trap nets set over 8 days on Fox Lake in the spring of 2015. Nets were set on April 27th and checked and reset in the same location each day until May 8th, excluding the weekend. Each muskie was tagged with a uniquely identified passive integrated transponder (PIT) tag. Of the 37 muskies captured, 1 was not measured and 1 was captured twice. Muskies were tagged with PIT tags in 2011, 2012, and 2013 for a previous population estimate study so some captured muskies already had a tag.

Of the 35 unique muskie that were measured there were 19 males and 13 females and 3 undetermined because they were not old enough. The average length of males was 40 inches and the average length of females was 44 inches with an overall average of 41 inches. The minimum length of males was 35 inches and 37 inches for females. The maximum length of males was 43 inches and for females was 50 inches.

The muskie population appears to be doing well in Fox Lake with fish equal to 50 inches in the sample. Additional spring large netting will be conducted in 2017 to further monitor muskie in Fox Lake. If anyone is interested in helping sample muskies as part of the spring assessment they are welcome to contact the Windom DNR office at 507-831-2900 to volunteer. Handling and collecting information from a large muskie is a rewarding and unique process that can be shared by all interested anglers.

INTRODUCTION

Fox Lake is a 1,041 acre lake located in south-central Minnesota near the city of Sherburn in Martin County. Fox Lake has a maximum depth of 20 feet with nearly 75 percent of the lake having water less than 15 feet deep. Minnesota lakes managed for fishing are grouped into classes based on physical and chemical similarities and Fox Lake is assigned to lake class 24. Lake class 24 consists of shallow relatively turbid lakes high in nutrients with a smaller littoral area and irregular shape. A 1.8 foot water transparency was observed during the summer of 2015. The following information outlines the information collected during the latest population assessment in September 2015 using 12 trap nets and 6 gill nets.


WALLEYE

The expected gill net catch rate of Walleye in Fox Lake is between 1.2 and 6.3 per gill net and the expected trap net catch rate range is between 0.3 and 1.2 per net. The gill net catch rate in 2015 was 5.7 per net which is within the expected range and nearly equivalent to the management goal of 6 per net. In addition, the trap net catch rate was 1.9 per net which is higher than what we would expect for lakes similar to Fox. Historically, the Fox Lake gill net catch rate has been sporadic with catch rates ranging from 0.5 to 45.2 from 1981 to 2001 with an average catch rate of 9.8 per gill net during that same time frame. Over the past 5 years, catch rates have varied to a lesser degree from 1.8 to 5.7 with an average catch rate of 4.0 Walleye per gill net indicating a more stable fish population. Walleye of all sizes are becoming more common in anglers catches with fisherman indicating the "best Walleye fishing in recent years" during the 2014 and 2015 seasons. The Walleye in the sample in 2015 ranged from 8.4 to 25.7 inches with an average size of 14.7 inches in the gill net sample and 16.7 in the trap net sample. Aging of ear bones (otoliths) from gill netted Walleye revealed 4 age groups (ages 1, 2, 4, and 6). Walleye in the sample were healthy. The outlook for Walleye fishing in Fox Lake looks good with a stable population where nearly 40% of the fish in the sample in 2015 were over 15 inches.


MUSKELLUNGE

In 2015, no Muskies were caught in the gill net or trap net sample. Muskie are not effectively sampled with gill nets or standard trap nets and the long-term catch rates from 2000 to 2015 reflect that with gill net catch rates varying from only 0.0 to 0.7 fish per net. Therefore, in 2011 a long-term Muskie study was started focusing on obtaining information leading to a population estimate that will help determine the ideal stocking rate for Fox Lake. Population estimates from the 3 year study put the population number of Muskie greater than 30 inches somewhere around 225 individuals. This would mean there is 1 Muskie about every 4-6 acres in Fox Lake. This indicated the population was doing well and many large Muskies were present in the lake. Additional population estimates will be conducted in the future, as large frame trap netting will be conducted during the spring biennially beginning in 2015. Every other year spring large frame trap netting was started in 2015. The 2015 spring large frame trap survey caught 37 muskies over the course of 2 weeks in April and May. Of the 37 muskies captured, 1 was not measured and 1 was captured twice that spring. Each Muskie was tagged with a uniquely identified passive integrated transponder (PIT) tag which allows us to tell how many times we catch a fish and how much the fish has grown since it was last captured. Muskies were also tagged with PIT tags in 2011, 2012, and 2013 for the population estimate study so some captured muskies already had a tag. Of the 35 unique Muskie that were measured there were 19 males and 13 females and 3 undetermined due to immaturity. The average length of males and females was 40 inches and 44 inches respectively with an overall average of 41 inches. The minimum length of males and females was 35 inches and 37 inches respectively. The maximum length of males and females was 43 inches and 50 inches respectively. The Muskie population appears to be doing well in Fox Lake with fish approaching the trophy category of greater than 50 inches.


CRAPPIE

Two species of crappie (Black and White) have been sampled historically in Fox Lake. Black Crappies have 7-8 dorsal spines and white crappies have 5-6 dorsal spines. In 2015, 366 Black Crappie were sampled in gill nets and trap nets and only 2 White Crappie were sampled in the trap nets. The catch rate of White Crappie was 0.2 per trap net, below the expected range of 0.5 to 6.6 per trap net. Over the past 3 surveys (2013 to 2015) only 6 White Crappie have been caught in gill nets and trap nets. The catch rates of Black Crappie in 2015 were 8.2 fish per gill net and 26.4 fish per trap net. It should be noted that this is the 4th highest catch rate of black crappie in trap nets in 30 surveys going back to 1981. The message is that black crappie abundance is increasing and smaller fish dominate the fishery at this time. The gill net catch rate was within the expected range of 2.5 to 16.5 fish per gill net and the trap net catch rate exceeded the expected range of 1.8 to 21.2 per trap net. Black Crappie ranged in size from 3 to 14 inches with an average length of 7 inches. Eighty percent of the Black Crappie were between 5 and 8 inches in the 2015 sample. With continued growth more keeper fish should be present in a year or two. In the meantime, large Black Crappie are present in Fox Lake and anglers should be able to harvest a few crappie bigger than 14 inches.


YELLOW PERCH

Yellow Perch in Fox Lake are the main forage for the Walleye and Muskellunge populations. Fluctuations in the abundance of the Yellow Perch population can lead to fluctuations in the Walleye and Muskellunge populations. The historical catch rates of Yellow Perch in gill nets range from a low of nearly 0 per gill net in 1992 to a high of 80.5 in 2012 and from 0 per trap net in 1986, 1989, and 1992 to 22.6 per trap net in 1997. The 2015 gill net catch rate was a more typical catch rate of 27.7 fish per gill net. However, over the past 4 years the Yellow Perch population has fluctuated from lows of 1.5 (2013) and 1.8 per gill net (2011) to a high of 80.5 per gill net (2012) and finally the current 25.0 to 27.0 per gill net in 2014 and 2015. This variable catch rate is not completely understood, but growth of aquatic vegetation beds over the last 5 years may give Yellow Perch a place to successfully hide from survey nets as well as from predators. However, targeting the weed line or these vegetation beds should make it easier for anglers to catch the Yellow Perch. The size of Yellow Perch in the 2015 sample ranged from 6 to just shy of 10 inches with an average length of 8 inches. As Yellow Perch continue to grow, anglers should be able to catch more harvestable sized Yellow Perch. Currently, the range of sizes is better suited for Walleye and Muskellunge forage and Yellow Perch are at levels that will allow for plentiful prey availability.


OTHER SPECIES

Other species of fish caught in the 2015 survey were Bigmouth Buffalo, Bluegill, Channel Catfish, Common Carp, Freshwater Drum, Golden Shiner, and Largemouth Bass. Of the species listed above, Bigmouth Buffalo, Bluegill, Channel Catfish, and Freshwater Drum are the most significant contributors to the fish community. The Bigmouth Buffalo in the population are mainly 8 to 11 inches indicating a strong year class and good forage for large Walleye and Muskellunge. Bluegill have started to become more stable in the fish community with a catch rate of 2.7 per trap net with sizes ranging from 3 to just over 8 inches. Channel Catfish are doing well in Fox Lake too and currently range in length from 12 to 29 inches with an average weight of nearly 5.5 pounds! Finally, Freshwater Drum are the most prevalent native "rough" fish in the population with a gill net catch rate of 57 fish per net. Freshwater Drum ranged in length from 7.5 to 18.5 inches with most between 10 to 15 inches. With an abundant Muskellunge and potentially expanding Walleye population, Freshwater Drum may increasingly become important as forage for trophy Muskellunge and large Walleye. Freshwater Drum are not often utilized by anglers or large predators in Fox Lake and are only just becoming susceptible to predation by large Muskellunge as those fish are now commonly above 40 inches.


SUMMARY

Overall, the Fox Lake fish community appears to be doing well with a diverse fish community that is seeing improvements in managed fish species abundance size structure. Further improvements in the lake for the fish community should focus on best management practices in the watershed. Improvements and education in land stewardship will often have secondary benefits to the lake in the way of quality and quantity of habitat. Generally, improvements in the quality and quantity of lake habitat will result in direct improvements for the fish community. Wise use of our natural resources makes us good stewards to the land and water that all of us use every day.

Fox Lake is a 1,041-acre lake located in Martin County near the City of Sherburn. Fox Lake has a maximum depth of 20 feet and is not aerated because it typically doesn't experience low oxygen levels. Growth of Walleye was normal, as mean length at age-3 was 13.6 inches, and Walleyes were plump indicating that food is not limited. Three year classes of Walleye were sampled including Walleye from 2013, 2014, and 2015, which all correspond to stockings of frylings and/or fingerlings. Walleye angling should be good on Fox Lake in the spring of 2017 as a good population is present.

Fox Lake is one of the deeper lakes in the area located one mile northeast of Sherburn. Fox Lake contains a diverse fish community and is one of the most utilized lakes in Martin County. The importance of the Fox Lake fishery has resulted in it being monitored annually. The lake management plan indicates walleye as the primary species of management with black crappie, bluegill, channel catfish and largemouth bass as secondary species. An important lake management objective is to reduce freshwater drum numbers so the other species can thrive.The walleye population looked good in 1997. The net catches indicated the population was 2.5 times higher than most lakes similar to Fox Lake. Walleye lengths ranged from 10.5 to 26.0 inches and averaged 16.2 inches. Seven year classes of walleye were identified by aging scales. Walleye aged from a year no stocking occurred must be from natural reproduction. We know there is some natural reproduction in Fox Lake. It will require more investigating to determine how much and how often natural reproduction happens. Walleye fishing should be good for a couple years.In 1997, we sampled good numbers of black and white crappie. When compared to lakes similar to Fox Lake, it appears to have a moderate black crappie population but a high population of white crappie. Unfortunately for the angler, many of those fish are still small. Black crappie lengths ranged from 3.7 to 11.4 inches and averaged 7.1 inches. White crappie lengths ranged from 4.1 to 9.1 inches and averaged 5.8 inches. The majority of the crappie were almost two years old and averaged about 7.0 inches. Given another year or two of growth, crappie fishing should be decent on Fox Lake.Largemouth bass and bluegill are two species that do best when there is good vegetation available in the shallows. Both species build their nests near vegetation in sandy areas. Largemouth bass and bluegill young feed on insects and fish that live on and around vegetation. Vegetation also helps young fish to avoid predators. Fox Lake has some vegetation but probably not enough to allow good largemouth bass or bluegill populations to develop. These populations were relatively low when compared to lakes similar to Fox Lake and probably will remain low. Although their numbers were low, largemouth bass and bluegill grow fast in Fox Lake. Fast growth rates for these species could result in a few trophy fish in the lake.The channel catfish population has really expanded in the last few years. Channel catfish have been in Fox Lake for many years but we usually only heard of a few big fish being caught. Channel catfish have not been stocked since 1986. Therefore, these young fish are from natural reproduction. When we used the spine of a catfish to age it, we found two, three, four, and five year old fish. Twelve fish were five years old and they averaged almost 20.0 inches. Channel catfish can grow to 20 or 30 pounds so be ready for a battle if you hook one.To promote and maintain healthy fish populations, pollution needs to be controlled. Fish habitat is directly affected by water quality. Nutrients, sediments and other waste can drastically alter the chemical and physical characteristics of a lake. It is important to maintain, if not improve, the water quality of Fox Lake through watershed management. Improved land use practices should insure that this fishery can be enjoyed by future generations. People often associate water quality problems in a lake with land use practices in the watershed but lakeshore property owners also contribute to water quality problems. For example, putting in sand beaches, removing trees and aquatic vegetation, poor septic systems, fertilizing lawns, and mowing lawns down to the lakeshore can also be harmful. Improved land use practices by everyone will help insure this fishery can be enjoyed by future generations.

Net catches indicate an increase in the walleye population since 1986, probably due to a substantial number of age two fish which were not large enough to capture during 1986. Gillnet catch indices for walleye are below state and local medians (25% and 37% respectively). Trapnet catch indices for walleye were substantially above state and local medians. Net catch indices for black crappie and yellow perch are above state and local medians. Net catch indices for northern pike and bluegill are below state and local medians. Net catch indices for freshwater drum remain substantially above state and local medians. Shoreline seining indicates very successful natural reproduction by bluegill.

Good perch fishing was reported by area anglers during the winter of 2001-2002 with fish in the 8 to 9.5 inch range.Channel catfish fishing in Fox has historically been a popular sport among area anglers. The abundance of channel catfish is still high for lakes similar to Fox. Lengths of channel catfish ranged from 10.4 to 21.8 inches and averaged 18.8 inches.The abundance of black bullhead is normal compared to lakes similar to Fox. Lengths of black bullhead ranged from 9.7 to 11.2 inches and averaged 10.4 inches. Black bullhead fishing has been popular in the past and the lake should provide good angling opportunities in the future.Other fish species sampled during the assessment included bigmouth buffalo, freshwater drum, common carp, quillback, white sucker, and yellow bullhead.To promote and maintain healthy fish populations, pollution and other inputs need to be controlled. Fish habitats are directly affected by water quality. Nutrient, sediment and other waste inputs can drastically alter the biological, chemical, and physical components of a lake. It is paramount to maintain if not improve the current water quality of Fox through watershed management to preserve this fishery for future generations to enjoy. A big step in improving the water quality was taken when the diversion was closed on Fox lake.

Fox Lake is a 1,041-acre lake located near the city of Sherburn in Martin County. Fox Lake has a maximum depth of 20 feet and is not aerated. Fox Lake's watershed is relatively small compared to the size of the lake (4 acres of land for every 1 acre of water). Watershed improvements and the closing of a diversion structure on the west end has helped water quality and has allowed aquatic vegetation to return, which provides habitat for several species of fish. In addition, curly-leaf pondweed can become abundant in the southeast area of Fox Lake when conditions are favorable. Fox Lake provides a unique fishery, in that it is managed primarily for Muskellunge and Walleye and secondarily for Crappie, making it one of only two lake systems in the Windom fisheries management area that provide Muskellunge angling opportunities. An annual fish community survey is conducted on Fox Lake and was done during the first week of September 2017 using six gill nets and 12 trap nets.

WALLEYE
In 2017, the Walleye catch rate was 14.5 per gill net, which exceeds the normal range for class 24 lakes (lakes that Fox Lake is similar to within Minnesota) and is tied for the 4th highest catch rate since sampling began. In addition, it is the highest catch rate since 1997 and is now part of a three year increasing trend of catch rates (5.7 per net in 2015, 9.8 per net in 2016). Part of the reason for a return in Walleye numbers has been a change in management from small fingerling (fryling) to fall fingerling stocking. As a result, five age groups of Walleye were sampled including Walleye from 2011, 2013, 2014, 2015, and 2016 which all correspond to years when frylings and/or fingerlings were stocked. Over the past several years, fingerling stocking has been more effective at surviving to catchable sized fish. Lengths of Walleye in the sample ranged from just under 9 inches to just under 28 inches and averaged 14 inches. Growth of Walleye was average for class 24 lakes with age 3 Walleye reaching 13.5 inches; however, this is a slow growth rate compared to other shallow southwest Minnesota Lakes. Walleyes in the sample were in fair health indicating fish are finding adequate prey, but could use additional food to fatten up. Future stocking of fall fingerlings will include the newly reestablished Lower Mississippi Strain Walleye from Lake Sarah. Eggs from Lake Sarah will be transplanted to rearing ponds as fry and then raised until fall when they will be stocked into Fox Lake. Fishing for Walleye on Fox Lake may be heating up! Until recently, Walleye were a bonus fish for Crappie and Muskellunge anglers. Now, Walleye can be targeted on Fox Lake with good numbers of harvestable fish present.

MUSKELLUNGE
Muskellunge were introduced in Fox Lake in 1999, were stocked again in 2001 and have been stocked every other year since 2004. No Muskellunge were captured in the annual standard survey because standard gill nets and trap nets do not effectively sample them. In the 2017 assessment using large frame trap nets, Muskellunge were captured at a rate of 3.9 per net per day. Muskellunge ranged in length from 11 to 50 inches and averaged 42 inches. The most recent population estimate indicates that there are 241 adult muskellunge over 30 inches in Fox Lake, with a range from 192 to 290 when factoring error into the model. Since 2011, 325 unique Muskellunge have been caught and tagged. Muskellunge fishing can be very good on Fox Lake at times. Larger fish are starting to be found in the sample. A trophy fish may be as close as one cast away on Fox Lake, give Muskellunge fishing a try on Fox Lake; just remember, a 54 inch minimum size limit is in effect (release all fish less than 54 inches).

CRAPPIE
In 2017, Black Crappie were captured at a rate of 56.2 per trap net, which is greater than the expected range of catch rates for lakes similar to Fox and the highest ever recorded! Additionally, the catch rate is greater than the long term average of 14 per trap net since 1981. Lengths of Black Crappie ranged from 5 to just over 12.5 inches in gill nets and trap nets and averaged nearly 7 inches in trap nets. Black Crappie are foraging successfully with many of the larger fish having "thick" bodies and excellent condition. The Black Crappie population is self-sustaining and stable with several year classes present based on length frequency in the trap nets. Black Crappie fishing will start to heat up over the next 3 to 5 years on Fox Lake as the fish continue to grow.

The White Crappie catch rate in 2017 was 3.3 per trap net, which is within the normal range of catch rates for lakes similar to Fox. White Crappie lengths ranged from over 6 inches to 10.5 inches and averaged nearly 8 inches. Although the two species of crappie can coexist, Black Crappie are dominating the Fox Lake crappie fishery and will make up most of the Crappie that you will catch. However, some White Crappie have the ability to grow very large with some reaching 15 plus inches in the past on Fox Lake.

OTHER SPECIES
The Yellow Perch catch rate in 2017 was 7.8 per gill net, which is within the normal range of catch rates for lakes similar to Fox. Lengths of Yellow Perch ranged from just under 6 inches to just over 8.5 inches and averaged just shy of 7.5 inches. Yellow Perch are currently at an average abundance, but may be more difficult to target with as many Crappie and other species present. Yellow Perch are Fox Lake's prey base for Walleye and Muskellunge. But, don't give up hope& some larger Yellow Perch can be caught while targeting other species.

The Freshwater Drum (aka Sheephead) catch rate was 41 per gill net, slightly below the long term average of 44.4 per gill net, but higher than the normal range of catch rates for lakes similar to Fox. Sheephead have historically been abundant on Fox Lake and continue to remain a dominant part of the fishery. Don't overlook a hooked Sheephead, they are an excellent food fish and should be utilized more than they are.

The Channel Catfish catch rate was 1.7 per gill net. Channel Catfish were large as lengths ranged from 23 to 29 inches and averaged nearly 27 inches. Expect a fight if you tie into one of these catfish!

Fifty Bluegill were caught in the trap nets and ranged from 4 to 8 inches. As aquatic plants start to return, so will Bluegill. These fish are creatures of habitat. Bluegill are making somewhat of a resurgence on Fox Lake and savvy anglers should be able to target them. Find pockets of submerged vegetation and fish near the edges, this should bring you luck.

Other species sampled included Bigmouth Buffalo, Black Bullhead, Common Carp, Golden Shiner, Hybrid Sunfish, Largemouth Bass, Common Carp, and Yellow Bullhead.

Prepared by Nate Hodgins

Presently Fox Lake is managed primarily for walleye with secondary management for northern pike, largemouth bass, bluegill and black crappie. The walleye population is high for lakes similar to Fox Lake but the average size is small. The average weight of walleye from our 1993 survey was just over 1/2 lb. and average length was about 10.5 inches long. The reason for the small average weight was because of a strong year class of 1 year old fish. These fish should be around 1 lb. for the 1994 fishing season. There is still a good population of walleye in the 14 inch and longer range however. Walleye lengths on Fox Lake ranged from 7.0 inches to just over 25 inches.Fox Lake has a fair number of black crappie present. The average weight of black crappie is almost 1/2 lb. Black crappie lengths ranged from 4 inches to 11.5 inches and averaged 8 inches. Bluegill numbers are low in Fox Lake but the average size of almost 1/2 lb. is very good. The average length of bluegill is about 7 inches. Fox Lake is well known for black bullhead fishing and 1994 should be no exception. Black bullhead lengths ranged from 8 inches to 13 inches and averaged 3/4 of a lb. This is an excellent population of black bullhead in the 10 to 13 inch range.

Fox Lake, near the town of Sherburn, is a 1041 acre lake in Martin County. Walleye and muskellunge are the primary species of management. Additionally, Fox Lake is managed secondarily for black and white crappie and channel catfish. Since 2001, the walleye catch rate has been somewhat lower than desired. In an effort to boost the walleye fishery, the Windom DNR Fisheries Office has stocked 2.2 tons of walleye fingerlings since 2001. A population assessment was conducted the week of September 7, 2004 using 6 gill nets and 12 trap nets.The walleye catch rate has been similar during the last 3 surveys and within "normal" range. At least 4 year classes of walleye were captured in gill nets and trap nets and averaged 18-19 inches. With the recent emphasis on walleye fingerling stocking and typically higher survival of fingerling stockings, it is likely walleye numbers will increase in the next couple of years. Although Fox Lake might now be less known for walleye, other species such as crappie and muskellunge might provide some excitement and action you might not find on other lakes in the Windom Fish Management Area.No muskellunge were captured during the 2004 survey. However, muskellunge do not trap well at this time of the year. A total of 251 muskellunge have been captured during commercial seine hauls since 2001. Personal contacts with local anglers indicate some muskies are being caught by hook and line at certain times of the year. According to the local anglers and commercial fishermen, many of the muskies captured are greater than 40 inches, growing well, and are in good condition. Another interesting observation from the 2004 survey was the lack of common carp and bigmouth buffalo caught in our survey nets and commerical fishing seine hauls. It is possible that the muskies are eating these species of fish as juveniles which may be a factor why so few were captured in survey nets and commercial seine hauls. Remember that muskellunge that are not 40 inches long have to be returned to the water. The black crappie catch rate was 11.5/trap net which is higher than the average (6.50/trap net). Total lengths ranged from 5.9 to 9.3 inches and averaged 7.1 inches. The black crappie size structure was similar to the 2003 survey. Historically, Fox Lake crappie fishing has been excellent in the spring. Based on the netting information from the 2004 survey, anglers can look forward to some descent action for crappie in the spring of 2005. The white crappie catch rates was nearly 52/trap net which is at least 7 times higher than the upper normal range (6.5/trap net). Most of the fish are in the 6-8 inch range and averaged 7 inches. Very few fish were captured greater than 8 inches. Like the last few years, crappie action will be fast but most of the fish (either black or white crappies) won't be huge.The channel catfish catch rate in gill nets was 8.3/set compared to 13/set in 2003. A fairly substantial year class of fish are in the 12-13 inch range. The sizes of fish have not changed significantly since last year which would be expected given the fact that they only grow a couple of inches per year. Total lengths ranged from 11.0 to 23.8 inches and averaged 14.6 inches. Channel catfish have not been stocked since 1986 which means the population is self-sustaining. These fish could provide some exciting action on those hot summer days when the crappie and walleye are finicky. A total of eleven species of fish were sampled during the survey of 2004. Other species were black bullhead, bluegill, northern pike, yellow bullhead, and yellow perch.To promote and maintain healthy fish populations, pollution and other inputs need to be controlled. Fish habitats are directly affected by water quality. Nutrient, sediment and other waste inputs can drastically alter the biological, chemical, and physical components of a lake. It is important to maintain if not improve the current water quality of Fox Lake through watershed management to preserve this fishery for future generations to enjoy. Prepared by Ryan Doorenbos

Fox Lake is a 1,041-acre, moderate depth lake located in Martin County near the City of Sherburn. Fox Lake has a maximum depth of 20 feet and is not aerated. Fox Lake provides a unique fishery, in that it is managed primarily for Muskie and Walleye and secondarily for crappie, making it one of two lakes in the Windom fisheries management area that provide Muskie angling opportunities. A survey was conducted on Fox Lake (starting September 8, 2020) to monitor fish populations using six gill nets and 11 trap nets. Surveys have been done annually since 1991 resulting in a great ability to track changes in the fish community.
Fox Lake's watershed is relatively small, with a watershed-to-lake ratio of 4 to 1, basically indicating that there are only 4 upland acres for every 1 water acre. Past watershed improvements have helped lead to the return of aquatic vegetation in some years, which provides spawning and nursery habitat for several species of fish. In addition, curly-leaf pondweed can become abundant in the southeast area of Fox Lake when conditions are favorable. Curly-leaf Pondweed was first documented during a survey in 2006. Recently, aquatic vegetation has been sparse and Fox Lake has been dominated by algae. Since the winter of 2019, Fox Lake has had poor water clarity and high levels of chlorophyll-a, which is indicative of an increase in nutrients (either internal or external in nature) leading to a persistent algae bloom, even under ice. Alkalinity was 240 part per million. For Southwest Minnesota Lakes, average alkalinity is 174 ppm with a 95% confidence interval of 165-182 ppm over the past 30 years. This indicates a very high alkalinity level for Fox Lake. Currently, Fox Lake is experiencing nutrient overloading and stress. A look at the fish community can help reveal the level of stress and potentially help pinpoint causes and reveal potential solutions.

WALLEYE
In 2021 no Walleye were caught in the gillnet sample. From 2015 to 2017, the Fox Lake Walleye catch rate was on a 3 year increasing trend (5.7 in 2015, 9.8 in 2016, and 14.5 in 2017). However, the past 4 years the gill net catch has been discouragingly low. The trap net catch rates during those 4 years has been decent with a catch rate of 1.0 in 2018, 1.4 in 2019, 0.9 in 2020, and 0.8 in 2021. The 2021 catch rate is within the interquartile range for similar lakes (0.27 to 1.24 per trap net). It appears during the week of sampling in 2021 Walleye may have remained near shore away from the gill nets. However, 7 of 9 Walleye sampled in trap nets were less than 11.5 inches. Looking at all Walleye sampled, lengths ranged from 10.1 to 15.9 inches and averaged 11.6 inches. Walleye in the sample showed less than desired body condition with an average plumpness which is an index to their foraging success. There did not appear to be a size based difference with respect to body size, indicating the fish were average condition across all sizes. The lake management goal was not met because the catch rate was below 6.0 per gill net. Due to low catch rates of Walleye over the past 4 years, 1,422 catchable Walleye adults (1,394 pounds; nearly 1 pound per fish) were stocked in September and October of 2021. Walleye fry and adults will continue to be stocked to boost the population. The Walleye population will continue to be monitored annually to assess the effectiveness of increased stocking in Fox Lake.

MUSKIE
Muskie were introduced into Fox Lake in 1999 and subsequently stocked in 2001 after which point they were stocked every other year from 2004 to 2018. In 2019, Muskie fingerlings were stocked again due to a surplus of fish produced in state fish hatcheries. No fingerlings have been stocked since 2019, but will be stocked again in 2023. The recent change in stockings have been a byproduct of inconsistent statewide Muskie production, COVID shutdowns, and statewide reprioritization along with improvement in lessons learned with Muskie management. Gill nets and trap nets are usually ineffective at sampling Muskie during our annual gill net and trap net surveys and that held true in 2021 with no Muskie being sampled. The last Muskie survey utilizing special large frame trap nets was done in 2017. In the 2017 assessment Muskie were captured at a rate of 3.9 per net per day. Muskie ranged in length from 10.8 to 50.1 inches and averaged 42.2 inches. The population estimate in 2016 (the last reliable estimate using 2017 as a recapture event) was 241 adults (192 to 290; 95 Percent Confidence Interval). Since 2011, 325 unique adult Muskie have been sampled and PIT tagged and 2,474 fingerling Muskie have been PIT tagged and stocked. Given the water quality challenges since 2019 on Fox Lake, a special targeted LTN assessment was conducted during the spring of 2021. Five Muskie were caught in 3 days of netting with 2 nets each day. Muskies sampled ranged in length from 39.1 to 48.9 inches with an average length of 42.2 inches. Three males and 2 females were sampled. Full-fledged mark-recapture sampling will occur in the springs of 2022 and 2023 to capture and recapture adult Muskie and determine if population numbers are similar to 2016 and if management adjustments should be made.

CRAPPIE
In 2021, Black Crappie were captured at a rate of 23.0 per trap net, which is greater than the upper normal range for similar lakes (21.2 per trap net) but down substantially from 52.75 per trap net in 2020. Additionally, the catch rate is greater than the long-term average of 16.9 per trap net since 1981. Fox Lake has had 7 successive years of catch rates above the long-term average indicating a return of good numbers of crappie. However, lengths of Black Crappie are lagging behind at this point. Lengths of Black Crappie ranged from 4.2 to 8.9 inches in gill nets and trap nets and averaged 6.6 inches in trap nets. The mean and maximum lengths are similar to the past several years indicating potential slow growth. Black Crappie appear to be foraging successfully as indicated by good body condition, but there is a decline in body condition for larger Black Crappie indicating some foraging stress and may explain slow growth. Overall, the Black Crappie population is self-sustaining and stable with at least 2 or 3 strong year classes present. The management goal was exceeded because the catch rate was above the desired abundance.

The White Crappie catch rate in 2021 was 19.9 per trap net, which exceeded the expected normal range of catch rates for similar lakes (0.5 to 6.6). Additionally, the gill net catch rate was 48.17 per net. The last time the White Crappie trap net or gill net catch rates were equal to or greater than 2021 was during the early to mid-2000's. This is a positive sign for the Fox Lake Crappie population. During the mid-to-late 2000's the Crappie population was dominated by many fish over 10 inches. This was largely due to hybridization that occurs when White and Black Crappie numbers are high. This may result again in the near future. Currently, White Crappie lengths ranged from 4.6 to 10.3 inches and averaged 6.4 inches in the trap net sample. White Crappie displayed the same decreasing body condition trend as Black Crappie. Unlike the past 6 years, White Crappie abundance is approaching and potentially exceeding Black Crappie abundance. When this occurs there is an increased probability of hybridization during spawning. Hybridization could lead to increased growth and maximum size attained by both species of crappie. Continued monitoring will evaluate growth and hybridization.

OTHER SPECIES
The Yellow Perch catch rate in 2021 was 0 per gill net, which is less than the normal catch rate range for similar lakes (2.0 to 27.9 per gill net) and unchanged from 0 in 2020. Catch rates of Yellow Perch have been characterized by extreme fluctuations since 2011. This variability in gill net catches is most likely due to environmental conditions and/or competition with increasing Black and White crappie populations. However, with only 1 Yellow Perch caught in trap nets in 2021 it is our plan to add some Yellow Perch broodstock to Fox Lake.

The Freshwater Drum catch rate was 87.0 per gill net, nearly twice the long-term average (45.9 per gill net) and above the expected catch rate range of 4.0 to 32.3 per gill net for similar lakes. While the gill net catch rate was the third greatest catch on record, the trap net catch rate was only 6.73 per net, less than the long-term average of 12.24 per net but above the expected normal catch rate range of 0.5 to 4.2 per trap net. Currently, the Freshwater Drum in the gill net and trap net sample range in length from 3.5 to 15.3 inches with an average length of 9.8 inches in the gill nets. With the exception of a few of the largest Freshwater Drum in the sample, all of these fish are potentially subject to predation by the existing Muskie population and the newly stocked adult Walleye. Predation coupled with potential commercial fish removal in the spring of 2022 may help to reduce Freshwater Drum abundance. However, this will not be a fast shift in abundance and could take several years with intensive stocking of gamefish.

Other species sampled included Bigmouth Buffalo (N=216), Bluegill (N=14), Channel Catfish (N=6), Common Carp (N=14), Golden Shiner (N=1), Quillback Carpsucker (N=1), and Yellow Bullhead (N=1). Of these species, Bigmouth Buffalo are of particular concern. These fish, while native, can over populate and act as a source of competition for limited plankton resources due to their filter feeding. They also have the ability to suspend sediments while looking for invertebrate food sources that can lead to internal nutrient loading and create poor water quality. The larger 2013-2015 year classes of Bigmouth Buffalo appear to be a possible driver of poor water quality on Fox over the last few years. While those year classes of fish continue to grow and move through the fish community, their growth appears to be slower than other populations in the Windom area. Continued monitoring will be done to track changes in numbers and species caught in Fox Lake.

Fox Lake is a 1,041 acre lake located near Sherburn in Martin County. The lake is about 3.5 miles long and has 9.6 miles of shoreline. The lakes bottom consists of sand, gravel, rubble and muck. Fox Lake is managed primarily for walleye with largemouth bass, black crappie, bluegill and northern pike managed as secondary species.Catch rates for walleye declined substantially since 1994. Local anglers reported 25 - 40 boats per day taking home limits of walleye from 1.5 to 2.5 lbs. in May of 1995. Despite this decline, the walleye population is still considered higher than normal for lakes similar to Fox. Net catches indicated that the population in 1995 was comprised of mainly larger fish. Walleye lengths ranged from 8 to 27 inches with an average length of 16.5 inches. The average weight of walleye in Fox was almost 2 lbs. Walleye fingerlings are presently stocked 2 out of 3 years and were last stocked in the Fall of 1995.Catch rates for black crappie were high for lakes similar to Fox Lake. Net catches indicate the population is comprised of mainly larger fish. Black crappie lengths ranged from 5 to 12 inches and had an average length of 8 inches. The average weight of black crappie was 1/3 of a lb. The black crappie population has increased since 1994.The bluegill population is considered normal compared to lakes similar to Fox. The bluegill population has increased since 1994. Bluegill lengths ranged from 3 to 9 inches and had an average length of 6.5 inches. The average weight of bluegill was about 1/4 of a lb. Net catches indicated the bluegill population was comprised of mainly large fish.The yellow perch population is considered normal to lakes similar to Fox Lake. Net catches increase since 1994 indicating a population increase. Yellow perch lengths ranged from 7 to 9.5 inches and averaged about 8 inches. The average weight of yellow perch in Fox Lake was about 1/3 of a lb.Black bullhead catch rates were high compared to lakes similar to Fox. Black bullhead lengths ranged from 7 to 13 inches averaged 11 inches. The average weight of black bullhead in Fox Lake was 0.5 lbs.To promote and maintain a healthy fish population, pollution and other inputs need to be controlled. Fish habitat is directly affected by water quality. Nutrient, sediment and other waste inputs can drastically alter the chemical and physical components of a Lake. It is paramount to maintain if not improve the current water quality of Fox Lake through watershed management to preserve this fishery for future generations to enjoy.

Fox Lake is located just north of Sherburn and is one of the deeper prairie lakes in the area. Fox Lake contains a diverse fish community and is one of the most important lakes in Martin County. The lake is managed for walleye as the primary species with black crappie, bluegill, channel catfish, and largemouth bass as secondary species.Walleye numbers have varied a lot in the last ten years. There have been years of excellent fishing and some years of moderate to poor fishing. Fishing success is determined by much more than just the number of walleye in the lake. Great walleye fishing generally occurs when the population is high, food for walleye is low, and the weather cooperates for anglers.Prior to 1998, Fox Lake received walleye fingerlings (1.5 lbs/littoral acre) two of every three years. Walleye fingerlings typically range from 5.0 to 9.0 inches (10-25 fish to the pound) in the fall and cost about 10 times more than walleye fry. Walleye fry are about a day old and the size of a mosquito larva. Due to the differences in survival for fingerlings and fry, more fry are stocked than fingerlings. Beginning in 1998, walleye fry were stocked at a rate of 1,000/acre, on a two of every three year rotation. Under this new stocking plan, it's believed the population can be maintained and probably improved. Since Fox Lake is sampled on a yearly basis, determining the effectiveness of fry stocking should only take three or four years.In 1998, walleye numbers were above average when compared to lakes similar to Fox Lake. Walleye ranged in length from 13.8 to 25.6 inches, and averaged 17.5 inches. After their first two years of growth, walleye averaged more than 13 inches. Management goals for walleye were reached in 1998. Walleye fishing should continue to be good for the next couple of years. Fish populations often fluctuate from year to year. Spring weather conditions, water levels, and the other species in the lake all effect the success of a given year class. Any increase in the available spawning and nursery habitat, such as vegetation and overhanging tree branches, should help improve the panfish populations.Black crappie catch rates have varied considerably from 1994 to 1998. The black crappie sample was dominated by the strong 1997 year class. Growth was good with fish averaging 7.5 inches in two years. Black crappie lengths ranged from 5.9 to 10.5 inches, and averaged 6.8 inches. Fishing for black crappies could be good after the fall of 1999 when these fish have grown to a size desirable to anglers. Largemouth bass and bluegill require good underwater vegetation to thrive. These species build their nest in sandy/gravel areas near vegetation. The young bass and bluegill feed on insects and fish that live on and around vegetation, and the vegetation helps young fish to avoid predators. Although Fox Lake has some vegetation, it is probably not enough to allow the largemouth bass and bluegill populations to expand. Largemouth bass and bluegill experience good growth in Fox Lake. These species can add to a fun day on the water, with the possibility of catching a trophy.The channel catfish population had been increasing from 1994 to 1997 but declined slightly in 1998. The expansion of the channel catfish population is a result of natural reproduction. Channel catfish lengths ranged from 10.8 to 21.4 inches, with an average of 12.7 inches. These fish should provide some exciting fishing experiences once they get larger.To promote and maintain healthy fish populations, pollution needs to be controlled. Fish habitat is directly affected by water quality. Nutrients, sediments and other waste can drastically alter the chemical and physical characteristics of a lake. It is important to improve the water quality of Fox Lake through watershed management. People often associate water quality problems in a lake with agricultural or industrial practices within the watershed. Although these can be areas of concern, lakeshore property owners also contribute to water quality problems. Some examples include putting in sand beaches, removing trees and aquatic vegetation, fertilizing lawns, poor septic systems, and mowing their lawns down to the lakeshore. Improved land use practices by everyone should insure that this fishery can be enjoyed by future generations.

Fox Lake is a 1,041 acre lake located in south-central Minnesota near the city of Sherburn in Martin County. Fox Lake has a maximum depth of 20 feet; however, roughly 75 percent of the lake is considered littoral (less than 15 ft deep). Minnesota lakes managed for fishing are grouped into classes based on physical and chemical similarities and Fox Lake is assigned to lake class 24. Class 24 lakes have associated fish abundance averages that then can be used to compare Fox Lake with other similar class 24 lakes. The lake to watershed ratio for Fox Lake is 4 to 1, which indicates a relatively small influence of the watershed to the lake. The water clarity for Fox Lake has improved since a water diversion structure was welded shut that brought more drainage to Fox Lake. Following the closure of the structure aquatic vegetation has returned; a 2.1 foot water transparency was observed during the summer of 2010.

Like many lakes in southern Minnesota, Fox Lake is managed primarily for walleye and muskellunge and secondarily for black and white crappie. However, Fox Lake is unique within the Windom Fish Management area because it is the only lake that is managed for muskellunge and the lake represents the southernmost muskellunge lake in the state, which provides a very unique angling opportunity. In addition, Fox Lake has been surveyed annually since 1991, which has provided an exceptional dataset to infer fish population trends and direct subsequent fish management decisions. Finally, unlike many lakes in southern Minnesota, Fox Lake has never been aerated during the winter and provides a more stable dissolved oxygen profile when compared to other area lakes. Ultimately, Fox Lake has proven to be a valuable and unique resource in southern Minnesota for lakeshore owners, local and regional anglers, as well as general recreational users.


In order to assess the management goals for Fox Lake, a lake survey with nearshore sampling was conducted in September 2010 using trap nets, gillnets, seining, and backpack electrofishing.


The walleye gill net catch rate in 2010 was 4.0 fish/net, which was the highest catch rate since 2000 and was within the expected catch range for this type of lake. The walleye in the gill nets had an average length of 11 inches and ranged from 9.5 to 17 inches. A 28 inch walleye was caught in a trap net indicating large fish are present in the lake. The overall size structure of the walleye indicated a population that is dominated by fish smaller than 15 inches. Currently, 3 age groups were present (1, 2, and 4 year olds) in the gill net catches with walleye reaching 13.5 inches by age 4. It appears the early stages of life are where the walleye are experiencing their slowest growth as they only reach 7 inches by age 1, and 10 inches by age 2. The overall condition of the walleye was good indicating a population of fish that is foraging successfully. Overall, it appears that the walleye population is at a low abundance and may be experiencing some growth problems. With that said large walleye can be caught in Fox Lake and trophy fish can be caught because the population may be slow growing and long lived.



The muskellunge catch rate in 2010 was 0.7 fish/gill net and 0.2 fish/trap net which are within and below the gill net and trap net expected catch ranges, respectively. These catch rates indicate that the population of muskellunge is at an acceptable abundance. The lengths of the 6 fish caught in gill nets and trap nets ranged from 24 to 34 inches with 5 of the 6 fish in the 22 to 25 inch range. Gill nets and standard survey trap nets have been shown to be ineffective at sampling larger muskellunge. Therefore, large frame trap nets are used in the spring months every 2 years to assess the Fox Lake muskellunge population. In 2009, a large frame trap net survey was conducted for the first time; 95 muskellunge were sampled. The muskellunge ranged in length from 33 to 48 inches with an average of 41 inches. A follow-up large frame trap net survey will be conducted in the spring of 2011. In 2009, 33% of the muskellunge sampled were greater than 42 inches. The chance producing a very large muskellunge is excellent in Fox Lake creating a unique experience in southern Minnesota. With two years of growth since 2009, the largest muskellunge in Fox Lake may be exceeding 50 inches. Trophy fish can be caught in Fox Lake.


Both black and white crappie are present in Fox Lake. The crappie catch rates during 2010 were 10.1 fish/trap net and 7.9 fish/trap net for black crappie and white crappie, respectively. The black crappie trap net catch was within the expected range and the white crappie trap net catch was higher than the expected range for lake class 24. From the late 1990s until the mid 2000s Fox Lake experienced high catch rates of crappie that were routinely near or above the high expected range for each species. While the catch rates were high during this time frame, the average weight per fish never exceeded 0.3 pounds. Currently, the black and white crappie populations have the highest average weight per fish ever observed at 0.8 and 0.5 pounds, respectively. The black crappie range in length from 3 to 14 inches and the white crappie range in length from 3 to 12 inches. Both species have a mean length near 10 inches. The size structure of the crappies indicated that the populations are both dominated by fish larger than 10 inches. With a large size and a lower abundance compared to previous surveys, the overall condition of crappie were excellent indicating the crappie populations are foraging successfully.


The black bullhead population has experienced a decline in abundance in Fox Lake since the early 1990s. In 2010, the catch rate was less than 1 fish/net for both gill nets (0.7 fish/net) and trap nets (0.5 fish/net). All black bullhead caught were greater than 7 inches and one fish was greater than 12 inches indicating a population that is experiencing poor recruitment as a result of reproduction failure or high predation on young fish. High predation is more probable based on angler reports of seeing schools of young bullheads near shore. Black bullhead in Fox Lake may be difficult to catch due to their low abundance, but the average size of fish caught may be very large.


The yellow perch catch rate in 2010 was 44.0 fish/gill net and was greater than the upper expected range for lake class 24. The 2010 catch rate was the second highest observed since sampling began. The total lengths of yellow perch ranged from 5 to 10 inches with a mean of 8 inches. The size structure indicated a population of yellow perch that is dominated by fish in the 8 to 10 inch range. The overall condition of the yellow perch was good and indicated the fish were foraging successfully. The yellow perch population appears to be at a high abundance with many large fish greater than 8 inches with no foraging related stress. Yellow perch fishing in Fox Lake should be good with many fish greater than 8 inches present in the population.


Other species sampled in gill nets and trap nets were bigmouth buffalo, bluegill, channel catfish, common carp, freshwater drum, golden shiner, hybrid sunfish, largemouth bass, and yellow bullhead. All species listed above were within or near their expected catch ranges, except for freshwater drum and golden shiner. Both species had abundances greater than the upper expected catch rates. The freshwater drum catch rate was 36.3 fish/gill net and the golden shiner catch rate was 2.2 fish/trap net. Freshwater drum and golden shiner can be critical forage for crappie, muskellunge, yellow perch, and walleye. Therefore, a high population of freshwater drum and golden shiner indicates an adequate forage base for the primary predators of Fox Lake. Additionally, the overall condition for all of the species listed above range from good to excellent, which indicates a fish community that is in excellent health.


The shoreline seining and backpack electrofishing caught 15 species of fish. In addition to the species listed above, shoreline seining and backpack electrofishing caught johnny darter, emerald shiner, and green sunfish. Age 0 fish sampled were black bullhead, black crappie, bluegill, bigmouth buffalo, common carp, golden shiner, green sunfish, hybrid sunfish, largemouth bass, white crappie, and yellow perch indicating some natural reproduction success. Interestingly, the bluegill age 0 catch rate was high at 576 fish per 50 foot seine haul indicating a strong year class of bluegill which may increase the abundance of bluegill in trap nets in Fox Lake in the summer of 2011.


The Fox Lake fish community appears to be healthy and abundance of primary management species is within normal ranges or higher. Further Improvements in the lake for the fish community should focus on best management practices in the watershed. Improvements and education in land stewardship will often have secondary benefits to the lake in the way of quality and quantity of habitat. Generally, improvements in the quality and quantity of lake habitat will result in direct improvements for the fish community.

INTRODUCTION

Fox Lake is a 1,041acre lake located in south-central Minnesota near the city of Sherburn in Martin County along the I-90 corridor. Fox Lake has a maximum depth of 20 feet, but most of the lake is 15 feet or less. Fox Lake has a small surrounding landscape that directly contributes runoff water supply to the lake (also called a watershed). Watershed improvements have allowed for the return of aquatic vegetation which is good for in lake fish habitat. Water clarity is improving with the ability to see down nearly 2.5 feet in the middle of the lake in the summer when other area lakes have very dense algae blooms causing water clarity of less than several inches. A Martin County Soil and Watershed District led program started in 2012 is focused on further improving watershed conditions for Fox Lake as well other Martin County Lakes. Improvements in the watershed for Fox Lake will continue to show up as improvements in water quality and clarity within the lake that will ultimately lead to healthier conditions for the fish community.

Like many lakes in southern Minnesota, Fox Lake is managed primarily for walleye and secondarily for black and white crappie. However, Fox Lake is unique because it is managed for muskellunge and is the southernmost muskellunge lake in the state, which provides a very unique angling opportunity. In addition, Fox Lake has been surveyed every year since 1991, which has provided an exceptional dataset to detect changes in the fish population that will help the DNR to quickly adjust our management decisions. Finally, unlike many lakes in southern Minnesota, Fox Lake has never been aerated during the winter and provides a more stable dissolved oxygen profile during winter when compared to other area lakes. Ultimately, Fox Lake has proven to be a valuable and unique resource in southern Minnesota for local and regional anglers, general recreational users, and for the local economy.

WALLEYE

Forty-three walleye were caught in 2012. The gill net catch rate of 3.5 fish per net was considered normal for Fox Lake while the trap net catch rate of 1.4 fish per net was higher than it has been in the past. Walleye gill net and trap net catch rates have fluctuated irregularly since the heydays of high catch rates in the early 1990's (1991 to 1994). The long-term DNR management goal of 6.0 walleye per gill net has not been reached yet so future intensive stocking of walleye frylings will continue. Frylings are 2 month old fish that are stocked in June at a size of 2 to 3 inches long. Frylings tend to have higher survival than just hatched walleye fry that are usually stocked in the spring. While the catch rate is still below the long-term management goal, the size structure of the walleye population is improving. Last year during the 2011 survey only 4% of the walleye caught were larger than 15 inches. Contrast that to this year's survey when 49% of the walleye caught were larger than 15 inches. The walleye in the 2012 sample ranged in length from 11 to 17 inches and the average size was 14.5 inches. The overall condition of the walleye in the sample was good with a slight decline to fair condition as the fish length increased. While there was a decline from good to fair condition, it did not appear to negative impact growth of the walleye in Fox Lake. The walleye in Fox Lake reach nearly 14 inches by age 3 and thus harvestable after only 3 years of growth. Overall, the walleye population appears to be reaching equilibrium with more large fish in the population. Continued walleye stocking should help to improve the size structure of the walleye population as it appears to be helping with fryling having been stocked since 2010.

MUSKELLUNGE

Muskellunge (nicknamed muskie) have been stocked into Fox Lake starting in 1999 with subsequent stockings in 2001, 2004, 2006, 2008, 2010, and 2012. No natural reproduction of muskie has been documented in Fox Lake so all fish present are from stocking. Muskie in the lake are now ages 3, 4, 6, 8, 11, and 15. Muskies over 10 years old have the ability to reach trophy size so potential exists for the Fox Lake muskie population to have trophy individuals present in the lake. In 2012 only 2 muskie were caught with 1 in the gill nets and 1 in the trap nets. Muskie are not effectively sampled with gill nets and standard trap nets. Therefore, in 2011 a long-term muskie study was started focusing on obtaining information leading to a population estimate that will help determine the ideal stocking rate for Fox Lake. Large-frame trap nets were used in 2011 and 2012 in the spring to capture muskie. In 2011, 140 muskie were caught over 2 weeks in May. The muskie ranged in length from 15 to 49 inches with an average length of 42 inches. In 2012, 45 muskie were caught over 3 weeks in April and May. The muskie ranged in length from 31 to 49 inches with an average length of 42 inches. Initial estimates from the long-term study suggest the adult muskie population (fish over 34 inches) has somewhere between 159 to 261 fish with 95% statistical confidence. This indicates the population is doing well and many large muskies are present in the lake.

CRAPPIE

Two species of crappie are present in Fox Lake, Black crappie and White crappie. The catch rates of black crappie were 20.0 fish per gill net and 10.4 fish per trap net and the catch rates of white crappie were 9.0 fish per gill net and 6.4 fish per trap net. However, catch rates of crappie are not good indicators of how well the population is doing. Crappie catch rates tend to vary widely from year to year and even from season to season. Usually, the population length distribution is more indicative of the overall health of the population. Black crappie ranged in size from 3 to 14 inches with an average length of 8 inches and 48% of the black crappie were larger than 8 inches. White crappie ranged in size from 4 to 12 inches with an average size of 9 inches and 68% of the white crappie were larger than 8 inches. Overall, it is safe to say that the crappie populations have balanced size structures with many larger fish present.

YELLOW PERCH

Yellow perch in Fox Lake are the main forage for the walleye and muskie populations. The 2012 gill net catch rate was 80.5 fish per net which is the highest on record. The size of yellow perch in the 2012 sample ranged from 6 to 11 inches with an average of 8 inches. This range of sizes should be adequate as a forage base. A large yellow perch population that has many fish across a wide range of lengths will increase the chances of sustaining large walleye and muskellunge populations.

OTHER SPECIES

Other species of fish caught in the 2012 survey were bigmouth buffalo, black bullhead, bluegill, channel catfish, common carp, freshwater drum, golden shiner, green sunfish, hybrid sunfish, largemouth bass, and yellow bullhead. Of the species listed above, bluegill, channel catfish, and freshwater drum are the most significant contributors to the fish community. Since 2010 bluegill have become more abundant in Fox Lake, which is coincident with the return of large mats of aquatic vegetation and improved water quality and clarity. The size structure of the population is fair with fish ranging in length from 4 to 9 inches with an average size of 6 inches. As the bluegill population becomes further established it should become a larger contributor to the forage base along with yellow perch and become a considerable component of the nearshore fish community in the lake creating a new fishing opportunity for bank anglers. Channel catfish are doing very well in Fox Lake and currently range in length from 18 to 25 inches with an average weight of 5.5 pounds. The abundant channel catfish population is the suspected reason why the bullhead population is not as prevalent as is has been in the past due to predation and competition for common resources in a similar niche. Finally, the freshwater drum are the most prevalent rough fish in the population with a gill net catch rate of 42.7 fish per net. Freshwater drum ranged in length from 6 to 22 inches with an average of 13 inches. With an abundant muskellunge and growing walleye population, freshwater drum will increasingly become important as forage for larger muskellunge and big walleye.

SUMMARY

Overall, the Fox Lake fish community appears to be doing well with a diverse fish community that is seeing improvements in managed fish species abundance and size distribution as well as increases in forage species such as yellow perch, bluegill, and even freshwater drum. Further Improvements in the lake for the fish community should focus on best management practices in the watershed. Improvements and education in land stewardship will often have benefits to the lake in the way of quality and quantity of habitat. Generally, improvements in the quality and quantity of lake habitat will directly result in improvements for the fish community. Fox Lake appears to be displaying the benefits of an improved watershed health over the past 10 years by way of a great fish community.
